1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to My First Opening Repertoire: 1.e4.   What do you need to master the opening phase of the game successfully?  It all depends on your playing level and experience. After studying this course, you'll have an excellent start based on White's most popular move 1.e4. This course provides you with all you need to know to get a head start in the opening.  Let's discuss the structure of the course and how to use it. We'll start with the chapter about general opening principles. We want to play according to these concepts, as they apply in almost all cases. Always have these principles in mind − it pays off! If you encounter moves that you have never seen or look wrong to you, thinking about general principles helps.   The next step is to build a core repertoire, the basic moves for all the main openings. We will examine the most essential and instructive lines for every reply to 1.e4. We apply the principles of opening play, seeing how they play out against Black's various responses to our first move.  Please note that we have a reasonably substantial chapter count, but each chapter is focused on the main points and can be studied quickly. Let's have a look at the chapter structure:   7 Chapters on 1.e4 e5 @@StartBracket@@incl. Intro/Overview@@EndBracket@@; 6 Chapters on 1.e4 c5 @@StartBracket@@incl. Intro/Overview@@EndBracket@@; 3 Chapters on 1.e4 e6 and 1.e4 c6 @@StartBracket@@incl. Intro/Overview@@EndBracket@@; 3 Chapters on other first moves for Black.  
The Intro and Overview chapters discuss the main ideas and concepts. The final three chapters don't share common ideas and thus have no such Intro/Overview chapter.   Each chapter consists of 1-4 'trainable lines', and the main moves can be studied using the Move Trainer. These variations are the most important to learn. They are selected based on how often they occur at the Beginner and Post-Beginner levels.  We have the most trainable variations on 1.e4 e5, followed by 1.e4 c5. This mirrors how often you will be facing the moves in practice. All trainable lines are annotated with detailed explanations about plans and ideas.  Often, you will meet 'clickable lines' in the text, illustrating concepts and sometimes covering how it might continue after the 'trainable line' ends. These clickable lines can be studied on your first tour through the course but don't need to be learned. You can focus on the main trainables first and, step-by-step, look through additional lines integrated into the text. Studying these lines is beneficial and recommended but optional.  After studying the core repertoire, you will confidently approach your games with strong weapons ready against Black's main replies. After each game, you should analyze it to learn and improve your game. One part should be to compare each game to your repertoire.  Do you remember what you have prepared? Or did your opponent play something that was not covered? Did you employ the opening principles correctly? Working on and answering these questions with the support of Chessable will help you improve your opening play and make you a better player overall.  Let's get to work! Enjoy the course and your games with 1.e4! }
