[White "1) Opening Principles"]
[Black "Opening Principles"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Let's talk about the most important concepts and ideas in the opening phase of the game. We want to follow these principles, as they apply in most cases. As with every rule, there are exceptions. But it would be best if you learned the basic principles first, which we do in this chapter.  ONE: Occupy the center with pawns and control the central squares @@StartBracket@@e4, d4, d5, e5@@EndBracket@@ with pawns. Controlling the central squares is a key strategic element. Controlling it has multiple benefits.   Imagine the starting sequence  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d6?  − we control the center, which gives us more space. Our bishops can be placed on more active  squares @@StartBracket@@like d3, e3@@EndBracket@@ than our opponent's. Our center also threatens to move forward. If Black plays a knight out to f6 or c6, we could attack it immediately.  The first move  1.e4  ,  clearly aims at controlling the center with pawns, following the first principle.  TWO: Develop your minor pieces. In their starting positions, our knights and bishops do nothing. We want to activate these pieces, 'develop' them. The knights are usually best placed closer to the center, which makes f3 and c3 natural spots for them. From f3 and c3, they control central squares and have more influence overall, looking at eight squares.  It is rarely a good idea to develop knights to the edge of the board, where they reach fewer squares @@StartBracket@@only four from a3, for example@@EndBracket@@. We also want to activate our bishops. It is usually a higher priority to develop the kingside bishop, as we want to castle to this side of the board @@StartBracket@@rule 3@@EndBracket@@.  THREE: Castle quickly, usually to the kingside. The move  1.e4  emphasizes kingside development, as it immediately opens  the f1-bishop. We are much closer to kingside castling than queenside castling, which occurs less frequently.  In most of our repertoire, we will castle kingside within the first 6-7 moves. There are exceptions, but as a general rule: try to castle quickly. It secures our king position and makes it much easier to play in the center, as we don't have to worry about our king's safety.  FOUR: Don't lose time in the opening. It is usually a bad idea to move the same piece multiple times in the opening. It is crucial to involve as many pieces as possible in the early struggle. We want to 'invite everyone to the party'. If one side has all their pieces in play while the other has just repeatedly moved the same one, it's easier to start an attack. It's just a group of attackers against one defender!  A specific case of losing time is moving the queen too early and too often.  Here's an example:  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  is the Scandinavian Defense. Black loses time with their queen. They have to move it again, neglecting the other pieces. Now Black should move the queen to a safe square. If they play  3...Qd4?  , we happily play  4.Nf3  , attacking the queen again. We get the knight development for free, while the queen is just moving around without any improvement for Black's position. We want to avoid multiple moves with the same pieces and early queen adventures!  FIVE: Pay attention to threats. We need to always consider what our opponents have in mind and what their concrete idea might be. Refrain from following the rules above, but consider what your opponent may have prepared. Is there a concrete threat?  A drastic example is the following sequence:  1.e4  e6  2.d4  Qh4?  , when Black jumps out with their queen in the second move. The move  3.Nf3  follows all the rules, but Black has  3...Qxe4+  , grabbing our pawn with a check. If we play  3.Bd3  or  3.Nc3  , instead, our pawn is secured,  and we can still play Nf3 in the future, gaining time on Black's queen. Black has violated rule four, but we don't want to ignore the threat to our pawn.   I want to look at a second example: After  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  , we attack Black's e-pawn. Black has to take this attack into account. If Black plays  2...Bc5?  they follow basic principles but ignore the concrete idea. We play  3.Nxe5  , winning the central pawn for nothing. We needed to move the knight the second time, but taking the pawn was more than enough justification.   These are the five basic opening principles that you need to know. If your opponent plays opening moves that violate these principles, you should check if you see a direct refutation @@StartBracket@@rule 5@@EndBracket@@.   If you don't, stick to the first four principles and make sensible moves that increase your central control, improve your pieces, and keep your king safe. Sometimes, silly-looking moves can't be immediately refuted. Accumulate smaller advantages and strike later once you are fully mobilized. }
