[White "2) 1.e4 e5 − Introduction & Overview"]
[Black "1.e4 e5 − Introduction & Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ The symmetrical  1.e4  e5  is Black's most popular reply. We played  1.e4  for a good reason, and Black argues that the same reasoning applies to the second player. Having a well-thought-out plan against  1...e5  is crucial because you will frequently face the move.  Let's discuss some possible concepts that White may go for. We have already studied the general opening principles in the previous section. How do we realize the opening objectives, like rapid development and control of the center? White has a wide variety of options, but most of them boil down to a few key decisions.  A. Can we manage to build a full pawn center? White would love to move the d-pawn  to d4 and support it with the move c2-c3, aiming to keep a pawn on d4 after Black captures on d4.  B. White may play d2-d4 without a c3-pawn supporting the center. White would play Nf3 and d2-d4 soon after. If Black takes on d4, White captures with the f3-knight.  C. White can play more modestly, not trying to play the pawn to d4 at all.   Let's compare and discuss these options. Plan A is difficult to realize in the early stage of the game.  Lines like  1.e4  e5  2.c3?!  d5!  or  2...Nf6  are uninspiring, as Black has a quick counterplay against e4. White has more sophisticated ways to play c3 & d4 later, though. This is a key idea in the Spanish/Ruy Lopez  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  , for example. The Ruy is a great opening, but there are better ones to start with, as play often develops quietly and is based on complex strategic considerations. The same applies to plan C.   I suggest Approach B for our repertoire: opening the center quickly with d2-d4. I suggest developing our knight first and then going for the d-pawn push. A sample sequence of moves is  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.d4  , which is the subject of two subsequent chapters.   There are some strong arguments in favor of this concept. Here's an overview:  We develop our pieces to natural, active squares. Our knights will be developed quickly, and we don't need to worry about our bishops. After the quick d2-d4, our c1-bishop will be ready to join the game. It is a simple-to-learn concept that can be applied in almost all cases. We open the position quickly, which leads to games emphasizing tactics and attacks. This is the type of game you want to improve your abilities and challenge yourself. Black might have done some opening study, but it was likely focused on other variations. Our opening concepts might be a surprise for them.    Let's talk about the chapter structure now. After  1.e4  e5  , I suggest starting with  2.Nf3  , when  2...Nc6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.d4  is the line we aim for. We need to examine what happens in this main line and study earlier ways for Black to deviate.   1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  is the Philidor Defense, a passive alternative for Black.  We fight it with a quick d2-d4, according to our general concept.    1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  is the Petroff Defense. We play  3.Nc3  , which will often be answered with  3...Nc6  , transposing to lines in the 7th or 8th chapter.   1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  Bc5  is the subject of this chapter. We have the shocking reply  4.Nxe5!  , which leads to favorable and fun complications.   1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  d6  and  3...Bb4  are nice for White, too. Black's position is too passive in both cases.   1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.d4  −  Black avoids ...exd4 in the first chapter about the Scotch Four Knights. Black should take on d4 @@StartBracket@@next chapter@@EndBracket@@, but we need to examine why the alternatives are inferior.    1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.d4  exd4  is the Four Knights Scotch main line. This chapter covers Black's most reliable defense to our  1.e4  e5  concept.  Even after Black takes on d4, they have to navigate some pitfalls.   Let's examine the dedicated chapters now! }
