1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ Black covers the attacked e5-pawn with their d-pawn. This defense is called the 'Philidor Defense', named after the strongest player of the 18th century, François-André Danican Philidor. He coined the famous quote 'Pawns are the soul of Chess', which, for the first time, acknowledged that pawns and their formations play an integral role in chess.   He also advocated the defense @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  , which is the subject of the current chapter. The move  2...d6  covers the e5-pawn but does not develop a piece and locks in the f8-bishop. Compared to Black's main options,  2...Nc6  or  2...Nf6  , the king's bishop can't join the game early on, for example, on the squares  c5  or  b4  @@StartBracket@@compare to lines like  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  Bc5  or  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nc3  Bb4  @@EndBracket@@  .  Therefore, the Philidor Defense has the reputation of being slightly passive, as Black voluntarily limits their options. How do we play against it? White's main candidate moves are @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  ,  3.Bc4  and  3.d4  . While the first two are good moves that follow basic principles @@StartBracket@@development@@EndBracket@@, the third option is the strongest. The immediate  3.d4  attacks Black's e-pawn and exerts more pressure, often leading to an inferior reply.  Let's investigate Black's options once the move is on the board. }
3. d4
{ This is White's strongest move. We open the center, prepare the development of the c1-bishop, and attack Black's e5-pawn. What should Black do now? Let's have an overview:   A.  3...exd4  is Black's best and most popular move.  They give up the e5-pawn and decide to capture our d-pawn. After  4.Nxd4  , White still enjoys some advantage, as we will see.   B.  3...Bg4?  is a mistake but still frequently played. Black goes for a tempting pin, but it falls short. Have you seen the famous 'Opera Game', contested between Paul Morphy and the duo of two noblemen during an opera performance in 1858? It started with this exact move sequence! We'll see that Morphy's play from the 19th century is still recognized as the best way to punish Black's mistaken opening concept.   C.  3...Nc6  is much better than  3...Bg4?  , but it gives us a wide range of good moves. I suggest playing @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2np4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  , which leads to a position that we investigate via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  d6  4.d4  , with a nice advantage. White has some other good options, like the logical moves @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2np4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bc4  or  4.Bb5  , but playing  4.Nc3  fits best to our concept.  Please note that  taking on e5 is not as promising as it looks at first sight.  After  4.dxe5  dxe5  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  , Black has lost castling rights, but this is less of an issue after queens were traded. In general, I advise  against trading on e5 in this central configuration @@StartBracket@@e4&d4 vs. e5&d6@@EndBracket@@, as we trade a more active pawn for a passive one and therefore help Black to gain scope for their pieces, in particular the king's bishop, which is limited by the d6-pawn.  D. Other moves are rare and best met with healthy development: we play our knight to c3, develop the bishop to c4 and castle kingside next. }
3... exd4
{ Black's best move. Black has no fully satisfactory way to keep the pawn on e5 and therefore captures our d-pawn. }
4. Nxd4
{ An easy move. We recapture the pawn and centralize our knight. A key idea of playing an early d4 is removing the e5-pawn to gain control of this central square for our knight. }
4... Nf6
{ A logical choice and the most popular move. Black develops the kingside and attacks our pawn.   You also meet the dubious  4...c5?  , which leads to a structure that we'll examine via  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  c5?  , a similar idea. I suggest answering @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c5?  with  5.Ne2  , which looks odd, but its idea will become clear once we examine @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  c5?  6.Nde2  , which follows the same concept. }
5. Nc3
{ Easy one: we cover the pawn and develop our knight.   Now we'll examine Black's best move  5...Be7  and the mistake  5...c5?  , a short-sighted attack on our knight. Black has some rare alternatives, like  5...g6  ,  5...c6  or  5...Nc6  − against all these setups, we can play as we do against  5...Be7  , by developing  our bishop to f4, followed by Qd2 and O-O-O. }
5... Be7
{ Black develops the bishop and prepares kingside castling. It is a modest setup, but Black's position is rather solid. Both sides' forces are not in direct contact, which gives us a range of options. }
6. Bf4
{ White has some good alternatives, in particular  6.g3  ,  intending Bg2 and O-O. I have a different idea though. The move I suggest is the most aggressive one. We plan to play Qd2 and O-O-O next. With our king safely positioned on the queenside, we may attack the kingside by pushing our pawns @@StartBracket@@f3&g4 comes to mind@@EndBracket@@. }
6... O-O { Black gets their king to safety. } 7. Qd2
{ We continue with our plan: secure our king on the queenside and attack on the other side of the board. }
7... Nc6 8. O-O-O
{ We have completed queenside castling and are ready to attack on the kingside. A sample line to show this idea is  8...Nxd4  9.Qxd4  Re8  10.f3  ,  followed by g4 and h4, the pawn storm on the kingside. It is difficult for Black to generate any counterplay.  Conclusion: The Philidor Defense is fairly unpopular because it is too passive. Black's f8-bishop remains inactive for a while, compared to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  , when Black often manages to develop the bishop to a better spot.  Black's relatively best option is the capture @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...exd4  , leading to the chapter's main line.  I suggest aiming for O-O-O here, playing as aggressively as possible. Black's modest setup invites a more ambitious play, which we should happily go for. This type of play is discussed more in this model game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Petroff 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nf6"]
[Black "Petroff 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Nc3 Bc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ Black goes for the Petroff Defense. Instead of covering their e5-pawn, they allow the capture and prefer starting a direct counterattack against our e-pawn.  The Petroff has a good reputation on the professional level, but is not played that often in amateur games. One reason is that some of the resulting positions are often labeled as 'boring', but this largely depends on the player's ambitions.   How to battle the Petroff? White has a fundamental choice between  3.Nxe5  ,  3.d4  , and the move I suggest,  3.Nc3  . Let's check why I prefer this move. }
3. Nc3
{ We cover our attacked e4-pawn, a simple and good reply to the Petroff.   This move makes a lot of sense in the context of our repertoire, as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.d4  is a cornerstone of our concept. By answering the Petroff with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  , we invite a transposition to this line. After  3...Nc6  4.d4  , we'd reach the starting position of the Four Knights Scotch. This looks like Black's best and most reliable option, but they often play differently. Let's have an overview:   A.  3...Nc6  4.d4  leads to the mentioned transposition and looks like Black's best bet.   B.  3...Bb4  is the best alternative, but gives White a small advantage − we'll examine this option with a trainable.   C.  3...Bc5?  is an incorrect gambit that we'll examine, too.   D.  3...d6  is possible, but not in the spirit of the Petroff. After  4.d4  , we'll reach positions that usually occur via the Philidor Defense move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.d4  Nf6  4.Nc3  , when  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  would transpose to our chapter on the Philidor.  We'll check B and C now, as the alternatives A and D lead to other chapters. }
3... Bc5
{ Black sacrifices their e-pawn for insufficient compensation. Let's grab the guy on e5 and see what Black has in store. }
4. Nxe5
{ Tasty chess! If you can win Black's e-pawn for no obvious compensation, you should go for it. But what was Black's idea after all... have they just blundered the pawn? }
4... Nc6
{ This is Black's best try and worth investigating. You sometimes see  4...d6  5.Nf3  , but Black has no compensation for the pawn at all. We are ready  for Be2 and O-O, and may play d2-d4 soon to occupy the center. }
5. Nxc6 { The simplest solution. The alternative  5.Nf3  is not bad either. }
5... dxc6
{ The only move, as  5...bxc6?  6.d4  looks terrible.   After  5...dxc6  , we have reached a position that usually arises via a different move order. Have you ever heard of the 'Stafford Gambit'? It arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nxe5  Nc6?  , when  4.Nxc6  dxc6  5.Nc3  Bc5  leads us to the position we currently have on the board.  The Stafford is an incorrect gambit, but it sets some pitfalls for White to navigate. If Black answers our @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  with  3...Bc5?  , it is likely that they were intending to play the Stafford and now try to transpose to their gambit line. We are happy to oblige, as there is more than one clean refutation.  So what to play now? It's a somewhat unusual, but strong move for White. }
6. h3
{ It is uncommon and usually wrong to move a flank pawn early in the game, as we have more pressing things to do − develop pieces, occupy the center, etc. Here, however, the little pawn move is essential and therefore covered in the course. Black's idea was to attack our vulnerable f2-spot with ...Ng4, which is a dangerous knight jump.   Here's a sample line to illustrate the dangers:  6.Bc4??  Ng4!  7.O-O  Qh4  and White already collapses due to the  threats on h2 and f2! To avoid these kind of disasters, just play  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/2p2n2/2b5/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.h3!  and stop Black's key attacking idea. Now Black's game is running out of steam quickly. Let's have a quick look at some ideas:  A.  6...Qd4  7.Qf3  stops the mate and plans d2-d3 and Be3 next.   B.  6...O-O  7.d3  covers e4 reliably and intends Be2 and O-O next. Once we have played d2-d3, Bc1-e3 is a logical idea to trade off Black's most active piece.   All in all, Black's pawn sacrifice is clearly insufficient. Make sure to remember the move  6.h3!  , stopping  Black's ...Ng4 attacking plan. }
*

