[Black "Petroff 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Nc3 Bb4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ Black goes for the Petroff Defense. Instead of covering their e5-pawn, they allow the capture and prefer starting a direct counterattack against our e-pawn.  The Petroff has a good reputation on the professional level, but is not played that often in amateur games. One reason is that some of the resulting positions are often labeled as 'boring', but this largely depends on the player's ambitions.   How to battle the Petroff? White has a fundamental choice between  3.Nxe5  ,  3.d4  , and the move I suggest,  3.Nc3  . Let's check why I prefer this move. }
3. Nc3
{ We cover our attacked e4-pawn, a simple and good reply to the Petroff.   This move makes a lot of sense in the context of our repertoire, as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.d4  is a cornerstone of our concept. By answering the Petroff with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  , we invite a transposition to this line. After  3...Nc6  4.d4  , we'd reach the starting position of the Four Knights Scotch. This looks like Black's best and most reliable option, but they often play differently. Let's have an overview:   A.  3...Nc6  4.d4  leads to the mentioned transposition and looks like Black's best bet.   B.  3...Bb4  is the best alternative, but gives White a small advantage − we'll examine this option with a trainable.   C.  3...Bc5?  is an incorrect gambit that we'll examine, too.   D.  3...d6  is possible, but not in the spirit of the Petroff. After  4.d4  , we'll reach positions that usually occur via the Philidor Defense move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.d4  Nf6  4.Nc3  , when  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  would transpose to our chapter on the Philidor.  We'll check B and C now, as the alternatives A and D lead to other chapters. }
3... Bb4
{ This is Black's best move if they want to avoid  3...Nc6  for some reason.  It gives up the e5-pawn, but Black gets enough activity to regain it quickly. }
4. Nxe5
{ We grab the central pawn, thank you very much. Black has not blundered the pawn though. By playing ...Bb4, they prepared to capture our knight on c3, followed by ...Nxe4. }
4... Bxc3
{ We will have a look at the immediate capture, as it is the most commonly played move. Black has various ways to recover the pawn with the same idea, but may do it in a different order. In all cases, our concept looks similar. Here are the main points:  They could play ...Qe7 or ...d6 to attack our knight. We should retreat to d3, attacking Black's bishop in the process. We want to quickly secure our king by playing Be2 and O-O. If Black takes on c3, we always recapture with the d-pawn. This helps to speed up our development, as the c1-bishop gains immediate scope.    This translates into various sequences, for example:  A.  4...d6  5.Nd3  Bxc3+  6.dxc3  Nxe4  7.Be2  ,  with O-O next.   B.  4...Qe7  5.Nd3  Bxc3+  6.dxc3  Nxe4  7.Be2  is a similar story.   C.  4...O-O  5.Nd3  @@StartBracket@@or 5.Be2@@EndBracket@@  5...Bxc3  6.dxc3  Nxe4  7.Be2  leads to the same scenario. These positions are a bit more comfortable for White. We'll see the same structure in our main line, hang on. }
5. dxc3
{ We always go for this capture here, as we immediately open our bishop on c1. }
5... d6
{ An important move! Black must avoid  5...Nxe4??  6.Qg4!  , which is a good line to know! We attack not only the knight but also the g-pawn! Black has no good defense against this double attack! }
6. Nd3
{ This is our standard retreat square in this line. Why do we go to d3 and not back to f3? It's not a clear mistake to move the knight to f3, but going to d3 has two advantages.  From d3, our knight can jump to f4 later, aiming at d5. This is a more effective spot than on f3. The second point is that, at a later stage, we can play f2-f3 to push back Black's centralized knight. }
6... Nxe4 { Black needs to regain the pawn before we cover it by f2-f3. } 7.
Be2 { Ready to castle. } 7... O-O 8. O-O
{ The initial opening phase is completed. We have castled and are ready for the next phase of the game. How does it continue? I want to show two ideas.   A.  8...Nc6  9.f3  Nf6  10.Bg5  illustrates the already mentioned idea to evict  Black's e4-knight.  The move  10.Bg5  is very unpleasant for Black, as there is no simple way to break the pin.   B.  8...d5  9.Nf4  c6  10.Be3  Nd7  11.c4  shows how Nf4 can help us to open the position for our bishops.   Conclusion: We answer the Petroff with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  , when Black's best option is  3...Nc6  , transposing to the Four Knights.  In this chapter we have examined Black's alternatives. The gambit move  3...Bc5?  is incorrect, while  3...Bb4  is solid, but comfortable for White. We usually get the pair of bishops in an open position, which is a good opening result. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Three Knights 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3 Bc5"]
[Black "Three Knights 3.Nc3 Bc5 4.Nxe5 Bxf2+ #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3
{ Black's best reply to  3.Nc3  is  3...Nf6  , entering the 'Four Knights Game'. This move, leading to a symmetrical position, is the most popular choice on all levels. On the master level, the move  3...Nf6  is more or less the only move ever played, as masters know that the alternatives are inferior.  Your opponents, however, will often choose one of the alternatives. In this chapter, we will examine  3...Bc5?!  , which looks like a logical move, but it has a severe drawback. }
3... Bc5
{ Black develops the bishop and increases control over the d4-square. It can't be a bad move, right? Well, 'bad' is a bit too much, but we'll see that it is a dubious choice, given that White plays the correct reply. We have a spectacular move now! }
4. Nxe5
{ Wow! We can take the central pawn, based on the idea  4...Nxe5  5.d4  , when the fork on bishop and knight regains the piece. Our knight 'sacrifice' is not a real sacrifice but rather a trade based on a tactic. Let's make an overview of what may happen after this shot.   A.  4...Nxe5  5.d4  is the most common scenario. We restore material equality and gain some advantage. How much of an advantage depends on how precisely Black will defend. There are a few traps they have to avoid!   B.  4...Bxf2+?!  is dubious but leads to fun complications. Black returns the minor piece and thus avoids the fork trick of line A above. After  5.Kxf2  Nxe5  6.d4  , we establish a strong center though. We'll have a closer look at those two lines, as there are no good alternatives. We have just captured Black's most important pawn, so they can't just play a 'random move'. Let's still have a look at some ideas.   C.  4...Nf6?  5.Nxc6  dxc6  6.h3  leads to a variation that we examine via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nc3  Bc5?  4.Nxe5  Nc6  5.Nxc6  dxc6  6.h3  − White is much better, as Black has no compensation for the pawn.   D.  4...Qh4?  5.g3  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/2b1N3/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qf6?  5.Ng4  are easily defused attempts for a Scholar's Mate. }
4... Bxf2+
{ Black realizes that  4...Nxe5  5.d4  looks nice for White and decides to give up the bishop immediately. Let's examine the situation after the forced reply. }
5. Kxf2 { We have to take the bishop, no choice. } 5... Nxe5
{ Black restores material equality. Note that they can't play  5...Qh4+??  6.g3  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4N3/4P3/2N5/PPPP1KPP/R1BQ1B1R b kq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qf6+??  6.Nf3  , when we keep the extra piece. }
6. d4
{ Here we go! We complete our dream pawn center and hit Black's knight, winning time. Let's evaluate the position. We have an excellent pawn center and the pair of bishops. These are two significant pluses. There is only one problem: our king already had to move and looks vulnerable on f2. We need to be careful until our king is in a safer spot.   Black's most popular choice now is a mistake. They often play  6...Qf6+?  , but this only helps us. We'll examine the queen check, but also the better move  6...Ng6  . }
6... Ng6
{ Black's relatively best choice. It is important to remember how to continue now. We must get our king to a safer spot and develop the kingside pieces. The best way to do that is to 'castle by hand', as we call it. We can't play the 'real' O-O anymore, but we can get to the same kingside setup by playing Be2, Rf1, and finally, Kg1. }
7. Be2
{ Remember this idea: we start the sequence Be2, Rf1, and Kg1 to get our king to a safe spot on the kingside.   You can also consider  7.Bc4  with a similar idea, of course. The move  7.Bd3?!  is less precise, as after  7...Qf6+  , our d-pawn is hanging.   How does it continue after  7.Be2  , though? A logical sequence is  7...d6  8.Rf1  Nf6  9.Kg1  to complete our 'castling by hand'.  Now we threaten Bg5 with an annoying pin.  After  9...O-O?  10.Bg5  , we threaten to destroy Black's kingside by taking  on f6, with Nd5 being the additional problem.   Black probably needs to play @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/3p1nn1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP1B1PP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9...h6  to stop the pin, but we are in great shape.  A good idea is Qe1-g3 to get the queen to the kingside. Later, we can play Be3, and increase the pressure on the f-file by doubling rooks. }
*

