4... Bxf2+
{ Black realizes that  4...Nxe5  5.d4  looks nice for White and decides to give up the bishop immediately. Let's examine the situation after the forced reply. }
5. Kxf2 { We have to take the bishop, no choice. } 5... Nxe5
{ Black restores material equality. Note that they can't play  5...Qh4+??  6.g3  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4N3/4P3/2N5/PPPP1KPP/R1BQ1B1R b kq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qf6+??  6.Nf3  , when we keep the extra piece. }
6. d4
{ Here we go! We complete our dream pawn center and hit Black's knight, winning time. Let's evaluate the position. We have an excellent pawn center and the pair of bishops. These are two significant pluses. There is only one problem: our king already had to move and looks vulnerable on f2. We need to be careful until our king is in a safer spot.   Black's most popular choice now is a mistake. They often play  6...Qf6+?  , but this only helps us. We'll examine the queen check, but also the better move  6...Ng6  . }
6... Qf6+
{ A very tempting move, getting the queen into the game with a check. } 7. Kg1
{ The safest spot for our king in the long run. This position is fascinating to examine and instructive because it illustrates some key concepts of chess. White has made some huge gains in the first moves. We have established a perfect pawn center and have the pair of bishops, which is a long-term asset. These points are valid, but our king's safety remains a problem.  There are various traps that we need to be aware of. If we navigate these traps, our position will be fantastic. We need to solve the short-term problems to preserve our strategic advantages, a typical struggle in chess. Don't be afraid of ghosts!   So what are the tricks and traps here? The first point to understand is that we are NOT immediately threatening to capture Black's knight! One line to demonstrate the idea is  7...Ne7  8.dxe5??  Qb6!+  9.Be3  Qxe3#  − a disaster!   Is  7...Ne7  a great move, then? No, because if we avoid the trap, Black is stuck with their problems. A good way is  8.Be3  , which secures the  sensitive a7-g1 diagonal. Finally, we threaten to capture the knight. Black has to retreat when we continue with the plan of Qd2, Bc4 and Rf1. You can also consider playing h2-h4 at some point, getting the h1-rook into action this way.   What about  7...Nc6?  A good reply is the similar  8.Be3  , which secures our strong center. Finally, I want to show the most dangerous trick that Black has. Let's see... }
7... Ng4
{ A rare move, but it can be extremely irritating to face. It looks like a blunder, but  8.Qxg4??  Qxd4+  9.Be3  Qxe3#  is a familiar pattern by now.  We can't take the knight... but at the same time, Black threatens ...Qf2#. What to play now? There is just one move that covers the mate and keeps the d4-pawn protected. }
8. Qd2
{ The only move that works! The queen must cover f2 and  8.Qf3??  Qxd4+  shows the issue with other squares. Therefore, we have to play @@StartFEN@@r1b1k1nr/pppp1ppp/5q2/8/3PP1n1/2N5/PPP3PP/R1BQ1BKR w kq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qd2  , it's forced.  The queen is on an odd square though. Our bishop on c1 is unhappy about the situation, but this is a minor problem. More importantly, we'll send Black's knight back home with h3 next, while Nd5 is looming too.   A line to illustrate matters is  8...d6  9.h3  N4h6  10.Nd5  Qd8  11.Bd3  , when we have a great position. A way to continue  is Qf2, followed by Be3 and Rf1. Black has a misplaced knight on h6, while our knight will find a good route to the kingside via f4. }
