[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3
{ Black's best reply to  3.Nc3  is  3...Nf6  , entering the 'Four Knights Game'. This move, leading to a symmetrical position, is the most popular choice on all levels. On the master level, the move  3...Nf6  is more or less the only move ever played, as masters know that the alternatives are inferior.  Your opponents, however, will often choose one of the alternatives. In this chapter, we will examine  3...Bc5?!  , which looks like a logical move, but it has a severe drawback. }
3... Bc5
{ Black develops the bishop and increases control over the d4-square. It can't be a bad move, right? Well, 'bad' is a bit too much, but we'll see that it is a dubious choice, given that White plays the correct reply. We have a spectacular move now! }
4. Nxe5
{ Wow! We can take the central pawn, based on the idea  4...Nxe5  5.d4  , when the fork on bishop and knight regains the piece. Our knight 'sacrifice' is not a real sacrifice but rather a trade based on a tactic. Let's make an overview of what may happen after this shot.   A.  4...Nxe5  5.d4  is the most common scenario. We restore material equality and gain some advantage. How much of an advantage depends on how precisely Black will defend. There are a few traps they have to avoid!   B.  4...Bxf2+?!  is dubious but leads to fun complications. Black returns the minor piece and thus avoids the fork trick of line A above. After  5.Kxf2  Nxe5  6.d4  , we establish a strong center though. We'll have a closer look at those two lines, as there are no good alternatives. We have just captured Black's most important pawn, so they can't just play a 'random move'. Let's still have a look at some ideas.   C.  4...Nf6?  5.Nxc6  dxc6  6.h3  leads to a variation that we examine via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nc3  Bc5?  4.Nxe5  Nc6  5.Nxc6  dxc6  6.h3  − White is much better, as Black has no compensation for the pawn.   D.  4...Qh4?  5.g3  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/2b1N3/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qf6?  5.Ng4  are easily defused attempts for a Scholar's Mate. }
4... Nxe5 { Black's best defense. } 5. d4
{ We regain our piece, forking two minor pieces. Now Black's path to a reasonable game is narrow. You'll meet  5...Bxd4  a lot, when we'll get a huge advantage, as we will see. Black's best bet is  5...Bd6  , but it is still nice for White. }
5... Bd6
{ Black's best defense and the only way to reach a playable position. } 6. dxe5
{ We restore material equality, an easy move. } 6... Bxe5 7. Bd3
{ The final move to remember. We develop our bishop and prepare kingside castling, a similar picture as in the main lines of the Four Knights Scotch, which also features the bishop development to d3.   Why to d3 and not to c4? It looks more active to place it on c4, but after  7.Bc4  Nf6  8.O-O  O-O  , Black has secured  the f7-spot and puts some pressure on e4 @@StartBracket@@taking on c3 and ...Nxe4 is an idea@@EndBracket@@.   After  7.Bd3  Nf6  8.O-O  O-O  9.Bg5  , White has a comfortable position. Our pieces are more active than Black's, and we have established an annoying pin. See the game Szwed-Romanishin for more information.   Note that we don't need to worry about  7.Bd3  Bxc3+  or similar lines that double our pawns.  Black gives up the most powerful piece in return for a weakening of our pawns, which is tough to exploit. Black has no pieces out to attack our queenside pawns while we gain additional possibilities. Later, we might play Ra1-b1-b5 or c3-c4 and Bc1-b2, for example. }
