{ Wow! We can take the central pawn, based on the idea  4...Nxe5  5.d4  , when the fork on bishop and knight regains the piece. Our knight 'sacrifice' is not a real sacrifice but rather a trade based on a tactic. Let's make an overview of what may happen after this shot.   A.  4...Nxe5  5.d4  is the most common scenario. We restore material equality and gain some advantage. How much of an advantage depends on how precisely Black will defend. There are a few traps they have to avoid!   B.  4...Bxf2+?!  is dubious but leads to fun complications. Black returns the minor piece and thus avoids the fork trick of line A above. After  5.Kxf2  Nxe5  6.d4  , we establish a strong center though. We'll have a closer look at those two lines, as there are no good alternatives. We have just captured Black's most important pawn, so they can't just play a 'random move'. Let's still have a look at some ideas.   C.  4...Nf6?  5.Nxc6  dxc6  6.h3  leads to a variation that we examine via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nc3  Bc5?  4.Nxe5  Nc6  5.Nxc6  dxc6  6.h3  − White is much better, as Black has no compensation for the pawn.   D.  4...Qh4?  5.g3  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/2b1N3/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qf6?  5.Ng4  are easily defused attempts for a Scholar's Mate. }
4... Nxe5 { Black's best defense. } 5. d4
{ We regain our piece, forking two minor pieces. Now Black's path to a reasonable game is narrow. You'll meet  5...Bxd4  a lot, when we'll get a huge advantage, as we will see. Black's best bet is  5...Bd6  , but it is still nice for White. }
5... Bxd4
{ A welcome sight! Black surrenders the bishop pair and activates our queen! }
6. Qxd4 { Black has a limited choice now, as we attack the knight. } 6... Qf6
{ I want to focus on this move because it introduces fun complications. Black has some alternatives though.   A.  6...Nc6??  or  6...Ng6??  7.Qxg7  is simple.   B.  6...d6  is better but after  7.Be3  or  7.Bd2  , White is in great shape. We prepare queenside castling and are ready to attack the knight  on e5 with f2-f4 later.  Note that  7.f4?!  Qh4+!  is annoying because we can't play  8.g3?  Nf3+! }
7. Nb5
{ A cool move to remember! First, we must be aware that Black's last move set a trap. If we'd attack with  7.Nd5??  , they have  7...Nf3+!  , winning our queen!   This is why  7.Nb5!  is so strong.  We attack c7, but at the same time, the knight does now protect our queen. Black has no good reply now.   A.  7...Kd8  8.Qc5!  is powerful.  We threaten c7, but also Qf8+!   B.  7...c6  8.Nd6+  is much simpler than  8.Nc7+  Kd8  , when Black can hope for  the ...Nf3+ discovery again.  After  8.Nd6+  , we gain some time with the check, so  8...Kf8  9.Be3  is allowed.  Our queen is secured now against the knight discovery, and Black's position is lost. Our d6-knight is dominating, and their king is stranded on f8.   Conclusion: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5  follows general opening principles but has a substantial drawback. We have the strong reply  4.Nxe5!  , which often leads to favorable complications.  It's important to study this chapter thoroughly, as some positions are excellent for White, but there are some pitfalls we must avoid. The best example is  4...Bxf2+  , which is great for White, but our king is vulnerable. We usually want a safe king, but here we must endure this inconvenience because the upsides @@StartBracket@@center, bishop pair@@EndBracket@@ are enormous.  The fact that @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc5?!  4.Nxe5!  is promising for White is a huge incentive to play @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  , compared to other options. Black will often get into unexpected trouble, as we have witnessed throughout the chapter. }
