[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3
{ In this chapter, we will examine  3...d6  and  3...Bb4  , which are Black's third and forth most popular moves. They are a welcome sight, as we'll get a promising position without any major effort. }
3... Bb4
{ Black continues their kingside development, a move according to general opening principles. It is still not as good as  3...Nf6  , the main continuation. The bishop move has a direct drawback that we can exploit. }
4. Nd5
{ Well, you shouldn't move the same piece multiple times in the opening... unless it is strong! Here it is a strong move, but why? The point is that we lose time by moving our knight again, but we will gain MORE time by hitting Black's bishop with pawn moves such as c3 and even b2-b4 and d2-d4 if they retreat the bishop to c5 or a5. }
4... Nf6
{ Black gets the knight into the game and wants to castle soon, a good move.   You also meet  4...Bc5  , when  5.c3  Nf6  6.b4  Bb6  7.d4  is a likely continuation, leading to the same position that we will see in a moment after @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/3Np3/1b2P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 5 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.c3  Bc5  6.b4  Bb6  7.d4  The same idea alse works if Black retreats the bishop to a5, it will lead to the same position. }
5. c3
{ Occupying the center by playing c3&d4 is an attractive idea − let's go for it! A good alternative is  5.Nxb4  Nxb4  6.d4  , opening the position differently. }
5... Bc5
{ This is the most important move to examine. It is played the most here, and the resulting position after our reply may also occur via the move order @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/3Np3/1b2P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 5 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bc5  5.c3  Nf6  6.d4  , as mentioned before.   Black has alternatives to  5...Bc5  , of course. A bad one is  5...Nxd5??  6.exd5  , when we attack two pieces and win one of them!   5...Ba5  doesn't lose a piece, but it's still a bad move. One good reply of many is  6.b4  Bb6  7.d4!  , when  7...Nxe4  8.Bd3  Nf6  9.Bg5  gives White a strong attack. Black has a hard time dealing with the pinned knight − more about this position in a minute, hang on. }
6. b4
{ We attack the bishop again. Here  6.Bc4  is a convincing alternative, based on  6...Nxe4?  7.d4  exd4  8.O-O  O-O  9.Re1  Nf6  10.Bg5  , which gives White a crushing attack. Black's pawn grab is too risky. }
6... Bb6 { Black keeps the bishop on the most active diagonal. } 7. d4
{ An important moment. Black's knight currently attacks our e-pawn, but there is no simple solution to this attack.   We could play  7.Nxf6+  Qxf6  , but we'd help Black with their development. Moving our knight again is not ideal. On the other hand, we don't want to cover our e-pawn with a passive move. The best solution is ignoring the threat to our e-pawn and focusing on classic opening goals. We occupy the center and don't waste time by covering pawns but rather want to develop quickly.   What about the greedy reply  7...Nxe4?  now? After  8.Bd3  @@StartBracket@@we can't play  8.dxe5??  Bxf2+  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/1bn5/3Np3/1P1Pn3/2PB1N2/P4PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nf6  9.Bg5  , Black is in trouble. The pin on the knight is tough for Black to handle. Just look at  9...h6  10.Bxf6  gxf6  11.a4  , which is a dream position for White. Black's pawns are a mess, and their king can't safely castle kingside anymore. It's clear that taking e4 is risky for Black. But what else? After 7.d4, we threaten  Bg5  and Black also needs to worry about the e5-pawn. There is no good solution for our opponent. }
