1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3
{ In this chapter, we will examine  3...d6  and  3...Bb4  , which are Black's third and forth most popular moves. They are a welcome sight, as we'll get a promising position without any major effort. }
3... d6
{ This move is unnecessarily passive. Black's f8-bishop looks rather sad now, as it can't be developed to an active spot on c5 or b4 anymore. }
4. d4
{ Very logical, as we intend to play the d-pawn after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d4  , going for the Four Knights Scotch. Now we'll likely get a favorable version of this opening, as Black is already committed to a passive setup. }
4... Bg4
{ Black develops their bishop and pins our knight. This is not the most popular move, but the two main continuations lead to positions that we examine via the Four Knights Scotch move order.   A.  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  Nf6  6.Bb5  and B. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2np4/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Bb5  exd4  6.Nxd4  . These two sequences lead to the same position, discussed via @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d4  d6  5.Bb5  exd4  6.Nxd4  , with a nice advantage for White. This pawn structure is also featured in this model game. }
5. Bb5
{ A strong move! We develop and pin Black's knight, which increases the pressure on the e5-pawn. It's important to understand that we don't want to trade on e5, as it only helps Black to gain more scope for their pieces.   After  5.dxe5?  dxe5  , Black would be able to develop  the f8-bishop actively. Taking on e5 is not a trade on equal terms, as d4 is a stronger pawn than d6.   The move  5.d5  is not bad at all, but closing the center leads to a less dynamic play. The move  5.Bb5  poses more concrete problems and gives us better chances for a direct attack. First  of all, we threaten d4-d5 now, with a deadly pin! }
5... exd4
{ Black is scared of d4-d5 and takes our pawn to stop our threat. The alternatives are no improvement.   A.  5...Bxf3  can be answered with  6.Qxf3  exd4  7.Ne2  @@StartBracket@@getting the d-pawn back next@@EndBracket@@ or @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/ppp2ppp/2np4/1B2p3/3PP3/2N2b2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.gxf3  , when  6...exd4  7.Qxd4  transposes to our main line @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/ppp2ppp/2np4/1B2p3/3PP1b1/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...exd4  6.Qxd4  Bxf3  7.gxf3  , which is excellent for White.   B.  5...a6  6.Bxc6+  bxc6  7.dxe5  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  is great for White. We are much better developed, and Black's queenside pawns are shattered and all weak. }
6. Qxd4
{ We have pinned the black knight, so taking it with the queen is possible. Now Black usually takes on f3, hoping to gain something by doubling our pawns. Let's examine the situation after our reply. }
6... Bxf3 7. gxf3
{ Taking the bishop is strong, but inserting  7.Bxc6+  bxc6  8.gxf3  is a good alternative too.  Let's discuss how it continues after the immediate recapture. We plan to castle queenside, so Be3 and O-O-O is the general idea. Our kingside is no safe place for our king @@StartBracket@@the doubled f-pawn@@EndBracket@@, which makes the queenside the best spot for the king. The open g-file is often great for a rook, targeting Black's kingside.  Conclusion: As usual, an early ...d6 is too passive.  After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  4.d4  , we get a comfortable advantage and an easy game.   The move  3...Bb4  follows general opening principles but has a substantial drawback. After the strong  4.Nd5!  , we see a great example of correct tempo play in the opening. Usually, we don't want to move a piece multiple times in the opening. The knight jump is an exception because, in the end, we win MORE time by attacking Black's bishop. }
