[White "7) Four Knights Scotch 4.d4 − Sidelines"]
[Black "Four Knights Scotch 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.d4 Bb4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ Black develops the king's knight, which is the best move. We have checked some less reliable alternatives in the previous chapter. Now White has some options. I recommend playing  4.d4  , which immediately opens the center and leads to an open position. Reaching this type of position is a primary concept of our repertoire. }
4. d4
{ Black's best reply to  4.d4  is  4...exd4  , which we will examine in the subsequent chapter. The current chapter deals with two alternatives worth checking:  A.  4...d6  is a passive defense but important to study. The resulting positions may also arise from different move orders. More on that later.  B.  4...Bb4  pins our knight, but it is a risky choice. We need to know how to tackle it though. Other moves make little sense, as we attack the e-pawn, and Black can't just ignore this threat. }
4... Bb4
{ A rare and slightly dubious move, but we need to check it. We can prove an advantage, but only with one reply! }
5. Nxe5
{ The only good move! White often struggles against 4...Bb4 because it is not obvious at first sight why you should capture e5 with the knight and avoid other options.   The problem with  5.dxe5?  Nxe4  is that Black immediately puts serious pressure  on our c3-knight.   Black is also happy about  5.d5  Ne7  6.Nxe5  Nxe4  , when the pin is annoying again.   Why is  5.Nxe5  so much better? Let's have a look at Black's most aggressive reply. }
5... Nxe4
{ Black wants to get the pawn back immediately. It's not a good move, but it requires a precise reply, just like the situation on the previous move. Does Black have alternatives?   An even worse option is  5...Nxe5?  6.dxe5  Nxe4  7.Qg4!  , which is great for us after  7...Nxc3  8.Qxb4!  Nd5  9.Qg4  − how does Black defend the kingside? After  9...O-O  10.Bh6  , we win material. }
6. Qg4
{ The best and most fun move to play! We attack both the knight and the g-pawn and enter wild complications. }
6... Nxc3
{ The only move available. The knight was attacked, and retreating or covering it failed due to our queen taking g7. }
7. Qxg7
{ Wow, what a mess! Let's make some sense of this position, which is very favorable for us!   A.  7...Nd5+  8.c3  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1pQp/2n5/4N3/1b1P4/2n5/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Ne4+  8.c3  is great for us.  We still attack the h8-rook and threaten mate, which will win back the piece with interest.  A sample line is  8...Qf6  9.Qxf6  Nxf6  10.Nxc6  Bxc3+  11.bxc3  , giving us great bishops in a wide-open position.   B.  7...Rf8  leads to an even more exciting position. We play  8.a3!  , attacking Black's bishop. If it retreats  8...Ba5  , then  9.Nxc6  dxc6  10.Qe5+  Qe7  11.Qxe7+  Kxe7  and now  12.Bd2!  gives us a large advantage after regaining the piece.  Even wilder is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkr2/pppp1pQp/2n5/4N3/1b1P4/P1n5/1PP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nxd4  9.axb4!  Nxc2+  10.Kd2  Nxa1  11.Kxc3!  , when we have a winning attack!  The main threat is Bc4 and Re1, aiming for the king! It is funny to see our king on c3 and the stranded enemy knight on a1, but this is irrelevant, as we strike first. This position is fun to explore, together with a training partner and supported by a computer. It's all attacks and tactics!   The whole @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bb4  5.Nxe5  Nxe4  variation is rarely played and extremely dubious for Black, but we need to be ready for a wild game. Studying the complications is lots of fun, even if you'll rarely get it on the board in a real game. }
