1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ Black develops the king's knight, which is the best move. We have checked some less reliable alternatives in the previous chapter. Now White has some options. I recommend playing  4.d4  , which immediately opens the center and leads to an open position. Reaching this type of position is a primary concept of our repertoire. }
4. d4
{ Black's best reply to  4.d4  is  4...exd4  , which we will examine in the subsequent chapter. The current chapter deals with two alternatives worth checking:  A.  4...d6  is a passive defense but important to study. The resulting positions may also arise from different move orders. More on that later.  B.  4...Bb4  pins our knight, but it is a risky choice. We need to know how to tackle it though. Other moves make little sense, as we attack the e-pawn, and Black can't just ignore this threat. }
4... d6
{ A passive and dubious move, but it is important to study. The position after  4...d6  and the following line may arise from various move orders, making it a fairly frequently seen line if you add up all the possible ways to reach it. Here are some examples: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  A.  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  Nc6  4.Nc3  Nf6   B.  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  d6  4.d4  Nf6   C.  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  e5  4.Nf3  Nc6   D.  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.d4  exd4  5.Nxd4  d6  6.Bb5  or  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  exd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  6.Bb5  leads to a position we'll examine via  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.d4  d6  5.Bb5  exd4  6.Nxd4  in a minute.   You see, whenever Black opts for an early ...Nc6 and ...d6, locking in their f8-bishop, we'll reach similar or identical positions. }
5. Bb5
{ An important move to remember! We don't want to trade on e5, as Black is happy about the simplifications.   After  5.dxe5  Nxe5  6.Nxe5  dxe5  7.Qxd8+  Kxd8  , we could spoil Black's castling ideas, but once the queens are traded, this is less of a problem for our opponent. Ultimately, we only helped Black because the trades activated  their f8-bishop. We want to keep this piece locked in and, therefore, should avoid the capture on e5.   Instead,  5.Bb5  is a strong move. We pin Black's knight and thus increase the pressure on  the e5-pawn. In addition, we also threaten d4-d5, attacking the unlucky pinned knight! This only leaves two options for Black: taking the pawn on d4 or breaking the pin by playing their bishop to d7. }
5... Bd7
{ Black addresses the pin, a logical move. Black can't ignore it, as  5...Be7??  6.d5  a6  7.Ba4  b5  9.Nxb5!  axb5  9.Bxb5  shows. We'll regain the piece with interest.   After  5...a6??  6.Bxc6+  bxc6  7.dxe5  , we win the central pawn and have weakened Black's pawn structure on top of that.   Back to the much better move  5...Bd7  − what now? White's best reply is not that obvious. }
6. Bxc6
{ This move is surprisingly strong. Why do we give up the bishop for a knight voluntarily? The idea is based on the following line, hang on. }
6... Bxc6
{ The only good reply, as  6...bxc6?  7.dxe5  wins the e-pawn for us.   Black must play  6...Bxc6  to set up a counterattack on our e-pawn. Now  7.dxe5?  is bad due to  7...Nxe4  , when we have achieved nothing. What to play? }
7. Qe2
{ A strong move! We cover the attacked e-pawn and accomplish several points. Black's e-pawn is now in danger again. They can't just play 'any move', as  7...Be7?  8.dxe5  demonstrates.   Can Black cover the pawn by playing  7...Nd7??  No, we have  8.d5!  to trap the bishop!   Black's most common and relatively best continuation is  7...exd4  now, when  8.Nxd4  leads to a position that we examine via the more common move order @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/1B2p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...exd4  6.Nxd4  Bd7  7.Bxc6  Bxc6  8.Qe2  , which is excellent for White. }
