{ Black needs to cover the knight; there is nothing else. Note that after  6...a6??  we should play  6.Nxc6!  , as it wins even more material than the other capture.   Let's return to  6...Bd7  − what to play now? Our reply is not so obvious. }
7. Bxc6
{ A strong move! Usually, you want to keep your pair of bishops − this case is an exception. By taking on c6, we preserve our well-placed d4-knight. The following lines show that we have an excellent game. }
7... Bxc6
{ This recapture is played most of the time. After  7...bxc6  , we have the strong move  8.Qf3!  , which accomplishes multiple goals. We prepare queenside castling,  strengthen Nf5 ideas, and we are ready to answer  8...Be7  with  9.e5!  dxe5  10.Nxc6  , which leads to a crushing attack. }
8. Qe2
{ We cover our important central pawn and prepare Bf4 and O-O-O. The position after  8.Qe2  is of special importance, as @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/1B2p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bd7  6.Bxc6!  Bxc6  7.Qe2  exd4  8.Nxd4  is a second move order to reach it. Black is in trouble now, as our simple plan is very effective.   A possible line is  8...Be7  9.Bf4  O-O  10.O-O-O  , when we are ready to launch a kingside attack based on moves  like g4 and Nf5. Black has no counterplay to speak of.  Black's setup, starting  with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6  ,  is passive. This allows us to play more ambitiously than usual. Going for queenside castling is a promising option here, as it allows us to have a safe king and still push the kingside pawns forward to start an attack. In many opening lines, it is not feasible to castle queenside, as it takes too much time to prepare. Black's passive setup gives us the time to play Qe2, Bf4 and finally, O-O-O. This idea may also arise via different move orders, as in this model game.
Conclusion: Black should answer  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d4  with  4...exd4  , as the alternatives don't convince. The pin  4...Bb4  leads to tactical complications, but Black is in danger. On the other hand,  4...d6  is too passive and gives us excellent prospects for an attack. }
