[Black "Four Knights Scotch 4.d4 exd4 5.Nxd4 Bc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ Black develops the king's knight, which is the best move. We have checked some less reliable alternatives in the previous chapter. Now White has some options. I recommend playing  4.d4  , which immediately opens the center and leads to an open position. Reaching this type of position is a primary concept of our repertoire. }
4. d4 exd4
{ Black's best answer is taking our pawn. We have examined some alternatives in the previous chapter, and they are too passive  @@StartBracket@@  4...d6  @@EndBracket@@ or tactically vulnerable  @@StartBracket@@  4...Bb4  @@EndBracket@@  . }
5. Nxd4
{ The obvious move to get our pawn back. Let's talk about the arising central structure for a moment. We have traded our d-pawn for Black's e-pawn. A trade of two central pawns is usually considered a 'fair' deal, as both pawns contribute to controlling the central squares.  We need to examine the remaining central pawns now. Our e-pawn is actively placed in the center, controlling the d5-square. Due to having moved both our e-pawn and d-pawn, we can easily develop our minor pieces and will castle kingside shortly.   On the other hand, Black has not yet moved their d-pawn. To complete their development, the d-pawn needs to be involved. Only one variation for Black accomplishes this goal and gives good chances to equalize the move  5...Bb4!  − why?  Black wants to play their d-pawn to d5, not just to d6, which is too passive. Only by pinning our knight does Black manage to realize this desired central pawn push. In practice, Black often chooses a different path and suffers. Let's examine the various options.   A.  5...Bb4!  is best and our chapter's main line.  B.  5...Bc5  is Black's second-best move, but we keep an advantage.  C.  5...Nxd4?  is very popular below the master level and excellent for White! This premature trade is a large incentive to play the Scotch, as you'll get it so often.  D.  5...d5?  is refuted by  6.Bb5!  ,  when c6 can't be covered with a good move.   E.  5...d6?!  can be answered by  6.Bb5  , when we transpose to the previous chapter. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6  5.Bb5  exd4  6.Nxd4  is the alternative move order to reach this position. }
5... Bc5
{ Black opts for a natural development move and attacks our centralized knight. This move can't be bad, and its theoretical evaluation is 'slightly better for White', not more. However, this is based on the assumption of close-to-perfect play afterwards. In practice, Black often stumbles right on the next move. }
6. Be3
{ It is important to remember this move. After  6...Bb4!  we must play  7.Nxc6  , which is the only good option. Here, after the bishop  comes to c5, we have the additional option to cover the knight, which is considerably stronger and gives Black plenty of options to go wrong. First of all, our move might look innocent, but Black's bishop is unprotected. This makes Nxc6! a serious threat! Let's have a closer look at some options.   A.  6...O-O??  ignores our idea.  7.Nxc6!  bxc6  8.Bxc5  wins a piece.   B.  6...Nxd4?!  @@StartBracket@@or the similar ...Bxd4@@EndBracket@@  7.Bxd4  Bxd4  8.Qxd4  is great for White. We are ready to castle queenside and launch a kingside pawn storm @@StartBracket@@f3&g4&h5@@EndBracket@@, a familiar idea.   C.  6...d6?  covers the bishop, but it is still a big mistake. After  7.Nxc6  bxc6  8.Bxc5  dxc5  9.Qxd8  Kxd8  10.O-O-O+  , we reach a fantastic endgame. Black has the weakest pawn structure you can imagine. Alright, what should Black do? The best move is far from obvious.   D.  6...Bb6!  is best, retreating the bishop to a safe square. Against this move, I suggest  7.Qd2  , going for queenside castling. After  7...O-O  8.O-O-O  Re8  9.f3  ,  we have the better chances, but Black's position is viable. The move 9.f3 not only covers our pawn but may also be the start of the kingside pawn storm, based on g2-g4-g5. }
