5... Nxd4
{ This move is incredibly popular in amateur games. We are happy about this trade, as it only helps to develop our forces. }
6. Qxd4
{ Our queen is now in a commanding central position. Black can't develop their f8-bishop to an active square, as we control all of them. How does Black even continue? }
6... d6
{ Passive, but relatively best. Black had no way to develop their bishop actively and accepted that this piece needed to be developed to the modest e7-square.   Couldn't Black have played  6...Be7?  No, because we are  threatening e4-e5, pushing Black's knight back.  After  6...Be7?  7.e5  ,  Black needs to return the knight to g8, as  7...Nh5  8.g4  is even worse. The same problems would arise after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/8/3QP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...b6?  7.e5  Bc5  8.Qf4  , when  8...Nh5  9.Qf3!  is a deadly double attack on knight and rook. }
7. Bf4
{ I like this aggressive move. We want to castle queenside next, followed by a pawn storm on the kingside. Moves like f3, g4, and h4 come to mind, starting our assault on the black kingside. In the meantime, Black has no active counterplay.   This type of position occurs frequently in our repertoire, for example after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d4  d6  5.Bb5  exd4  6.Nxd4  Bd7  7.Bxc6  Bxc6  8.Qe2  , discussed in the previous chapter; it follows the same mindset. }
