5... Bb4
{ Black's best move and the only one that leads to a fully satisfactory game for our opponent. The move not only addresses Black's need to develop the kingside and castle but also fights for the control of d5 by pinning our knight. At the same time, Black exerts pressure on our e-pawn. How to react? }
6. Nxc6
{ An important move, and the only good one. Black had increased the pressure on our e-pawn, a threat we must address.   The move  6.f3?!  is too slow due to  6...d5!  , when Black manages to open the game after we have lost time and weakened ourselves by playing the f-pawn.   The best way to cover the e-pawn is developing our bishop to d3, but  6.Bd3??  Nxd4  is a sad sight. This leads to the conclusion that we must take on c6 first, then develop our bishop. }
6... bxc6
{ Capturing towards the center is Black's best move.   6...dxc6?!  7.Qxd8+  gives up castling rights for no benefit, and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2N2n2/8/1b2P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bxc3?!  surrenders the bishop pair prematurely. We'll discuss this situation in a moment because after  6...bxc6  7.Bd3  , Black will have the same option again. }
7. Bd3
{ We develop, protect our pawn and prepare castling − all in one move. Let's talk about Black's options now and how to react.   A.  7...Bxc3+?!  8.bxc3  is a questionable trade. Our pawn structure is damaged, but our dark-squared bishop gains in strength now. This is illustrated by  8...d5?  9.exd5  cxd5  10.Ba3!  , when Black can't castle. This would be a complete disaster, so  8...O-O  is a better choice. After  9.O-O  d6  , we have  10.Bg5!  , which shows the second annoying post for our bishop. We pin Black's knight, and it is tough for Black to untangle.  They can play ...h6 &... g5, but the 'cure' would be worse than the disease − Black's king won't be happy about it!   B. A better try for Black is  7...O-O  8.O-O  Re8  , but  9.Bg5!  sets up an annoying pin again. Black may play  9...h6  10.Bh4  g5  11.Bg3  Bxc3  12.bxc3  Nxe4  , but  13.Qh5!  gives us a strong attack against Black's weakened king.   C. The most reliable defense for Black is  7...d5  or  7...O-O  8.O-O  d5  , opening the center. After  9.exd5  cxd5  , White has a good choice of moves. I suggest  10.Bg5  , again setting up an annoying pin. We want to increase the pressure on Black's kingside @@StartBracket@@Qf3 is a key idea@@EndBracket@@ and use the open e-file. All of our pieces enjoy active positions, and our pawn structure is ideal, without any weaknesses.   Conclusion: Black's absolute best way to play after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  is entering the Four Knights  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  Nf6  and then answer  4.d4  with  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  Bb4!  , as examined in the main line of the current chapter. In this case, Black has good chances to equalize the game.  We still have no reasons to complain, as our position allows us to develop the pieces to active squares, our pawn structure is sound, and our king is secure. In practice, Black will often choose a different path. The current chapter shows that Black can't get equal chances in these cases and often gets in serious trouble quickly. }
