[White "9) 1.e4 c5 − Introduction & Overview"]
[Black "1.e4 c5 − Introduction & Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ The following five chapters are about  1.e4  c5  , the Sicilian Defense. The Sicilian is very popular on all levels of play, as it is considered a great weapon for Black to fight for a win. Let's discuss the idea of the Sicilian Defense first, and then we'll talk about our choice against it.  What does Black want to achieve with their pawn move? Looking at the opening principles, we see that  1.e4  c5  exerts some influence in the center:  the d4-square. On the other hand, it does not help much with developing pieces or preparing kingside castling. If you compare it to  1.e4  e5  , you'll see that the symmetrical answer prepares the bishop development, which makes it easier for Black to prepare to castle quickly. In the Sicilian, Black usually needs more time to complete their development and castle. This sounds like a risky or possibly even bad approach, as it contradicts general opening rules.  Let's discuss why the Sicilian is still a good opening.  With the first move, Black takes control of the d4-square. This makes it more difficult for White to establish a full pawn center of e4&d4. The direct  1.e4  c5  2.d4  cxd4  3.Qxd4  Nc6  is dubious, as we'd need to move our queen multiple times for no benefit. On the other hand, we'd like to involve our d-pawn  to open up the c1-bishop. This leads to three main, basic concepts that White could go for.   A. Play  2.Nf3  to prepare d2-d4 and open the center. This approach is called the 'Open Sicilian'; a popular way for White to play. The drawback for White, from a practical point of view, is that Black has more than 10@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ viable options to choose from.  After  2.Nf3  , they can play  2...d6  ,  2...Nc6  ,  2...e6  ,  2...g6  − all good moves. But there are further splits soon after, and Black gets to choose what they want to play. The 'Open Sicilian', with famous lines like 'Najdorf', 'Dragon' or 'Sveshnikov', is fascinating but tough to master if you want to start building a repertoire.   B. White can play a more modest setup, giving up on playing the d-pawn to d4. There are various lines like this, often starting with  2.Nc3  − the 'Closed Sicilian'. Some of these ideas are interesting but rather sophisticated. I wanted to recommend something more straightforward and following our opening principles.  C.  White can prepare the move d2-d4 with c2-c3, intending to recapture d4 with the c-pawn. The basic idea would be  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.cxd4  , when we have accomplished our dream pawn duo  of e4&d4. There are various ways to employ the c3 idea. You may start with  2.Nf3  and play c3 later, for example. The simplest way to do it is by playing  2.c3  immediately, the 'Alapin Variation'.  You can already tell that I suggest option C in our repertoire. It is much easier to learn than A or B and is very effective in practice. Black often wants to get their favorite Dragon/Najdorf etc. on the board, but only has a vague idea of how to battle our choice.  We cover the Alapin in 5 chapters, looking at the most popular replies. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  allows  3.d4  , realizing our plan, while @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.d4  is the same story. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  3.d4  again builds the full center.   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d5  attacks our pawn, we need to take, while  2...Nf6  also attacks our pawn. We go  3.e5  to attack the knight.  The first three moves are very popular below the master level. The main reason is that Black often continues with the same move they had intended to play after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , but this simple approach can easily backfire. Our concept of building a full center with  2.c3  and d4 next is completely different from the Open Sicilian that Black primarily expected to happen.   Black's chances in  2...Nc6  ,  2...d6  , and  2...e6  are objectively satisfactory, but they often go wrong quickly. It is tough to play against a full center if you don't know exactly what to do.  Black's best moves are  2...d5  and  2...Nf6  . The common feature of those lines is that Black attacks our e-pawn, forcing it to move. We don't have time to  play d2-d4 to create our desired central pawn duo. Before you continue with the five chapters, a quick word about possible alternatives. Black may play moves like  2...g6  ,  2...b6  or  2...a6  . We continue with  3.d4  in all cases, following our concept. If you encounter moves you don't know, follow the general opening principles. }
