1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nc6
{ Black develops the knight, a logical move. It follows general opening principles and can't be bad. A closer look reveals that it is objectively fine, but Black needs to know or find the correct path on the next moves, or they will get in trouble. Let's examine these possible pitfalls that Black needs to avoid. }
3. d4
{ That was our plan: build a perfect pawn center. Now we get to the first crucial moment. After  3.d4  , Black's best reply is rarely played. It is  3...d5!  , when  4.exd5  Qxd5  transposes to a position we examine via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  Nc6  , a viable main line for Black.   In practice, however, Black usually trades on d4, which is less precise. We'll look at this move, but also at  3...e6?  , which is a mistake. }
3... e6 { The move ...e6 is common in the Sicilian, but mistimed here. } 4. d5
{ Of course. We are happy to gain more space in the center and push around Black's knight. This line is similar to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/3PP3/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...cxd4  4.cxd4  e6  5.d5  , but Black is in even worse shape here.  The pawn on c5 worsens the situation for the f8-bishop. }
4... exd5
{ Or  4...Ne5?  5.f4  Ng6  6.d6  , which looks even worse. How does Black ever get developed?  The d6-pawn is a real pain! }
5. exd5 Ne5
{ Black has to avoid  5...Nce7??  6.d6  Ng6  7.Qe2+  , winning us a piece! } 6.
Nf3
{ The simplest solution to get castled quickly. After  6...Nxf3+  7.Qxf3  , White has a large advantage. We have much more space due to the advanced d-pawn, giving us good spots for our pieces. The bishops would be well-placed on d3 and f4, while c4 looks like a good knight outpost. The easy development helps with castling kingside quickly. This also means that we will be faster in using the only open file − a very nice opening result. }
