1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nc6
{ Black develops the knight, a logical move. It follows general opening principles and can't be bad. A closer look reveals that it is objectively fine, but Black needs to know or find the correct path on the next moves, or they will get in trouble. Let's examine these possible pitfalls that Black needs to avoid. }
3. d4
{ That was our plan: build a perfect pawn center. Now we get to the first crucial moment. After  3.d4  , Black's best reply is rarely played. It is  3...d5!  , when  4.exd5  Qxd5  transposes to a position we examine via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  Nc6  , a viable main line for Black.   In practice, however, Black usually trades on d4, which is less precise. We'll look at this move, but also at  3...e6?  , which is a mistake. }
3... cxd4
{ A natural move, but we are always happy about this trade, as we are granted the additional option Nc3. }
4. cxd4
{ And we have reached the second critical position of this line. Now Black's only way to a reasonable game is  4...d5  , when  5.exd5  Qxd5  6.Nf3  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  cxd4  5.cxd4  Nc6  6.Nf3  , which we cover in a different chapter. We have better chances in this line, but it is still Black's best option.   If they don't play  4...d5  , they are in trouble. We'll now examine  4...e6?!  and  4...d6?!  to illustrate the problems. }
4... d6
{ A passive move that does not fight for an equal share of the center. } 5. d5
{ Gaining space and time. } 5... Ne5 6. f4
{ The most aggressive way. There is nothing wrong about  6.Nc3  or a similar development, but our pawn center looks crushing after pushing the f-pawn.  After Black retreats their knight, we will develop our knights to f3 and c3, and prepare kingside castling next. Black has difficulty developing, as their pieces stand on each other's toes. }
6... Ng6 7. Nc3
{ A good move, but  7.Nf3  is just as good. We want to develop the two knights to their most active squares and the order is not important. Black is in severe trouble now, as they can't develop their kingside easily. Let's check possible continuations after  7.Nc3  .  A.  7...Nf6  8.Nf3  (we threaten e4-e5 now!)  8...e5  @@StartBracket@@or  8...e6  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/3p1nn1/3Pp3/4PP2/2N2N2/PP4PP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq e6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.dxe6  fxe6  10.Bc4  is awkward for Black, as their central pawns are weak and the king won't be able to castle easily. After  10...Be7  11.Nd4  , Black has no satisfactory move.   B.  7...e5  8.dxe6  fxe6  9.Nf3  likely transposes to line A above. Black has no good way to develop the kingside without moving the e-pawn, which will create weaknesses. }
