4. cxd4
{ And we have reached the second critical position of this line. Now Black's only way to a reasonable game is  4...d5  , when  5.exd5  Qxd5  6.Nf3  transposes to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  cxd4  5.cxd4  Nc6  6.Nf3  , which we cover in a different chapter. We have better chances in this line, but it is still Black's best option.   If they don't play  4...d5  , they are in trouble. We'll now examine  4...e6?!  and  4...d6?!  to illustrate the problems. }
