1. e4 c5 2. c3 d6
{ Black goes for  2...d6  , which prepares the attack on our e-pawn  with ...Nf6. Black argues that  2...Nf6  is answered by  3.e5  , so they want to prepare the knight jump by covering  the e5-square. This concept makes sense but does not stop us from building and maintaining the strong pawn duo e4&d4. }
3. d4
{ Easy, that was our idea. Now we'll focus on  3...Nf6  , which attacks our e-pawn. Black also frequently inserts  3...cxd4  4.cxd4  and then plays  4...Nf6  , when  5.Bd3  leads to positions that we'll examine in a moment. }
3... Nf6 { Black attacks our e-pawn, the idea of the previous move. } 4. Bd3
{ We cover our central pawn and get one move closer to kingside castling. This move looks very logical and leads to positions that are simple to play. }
4... cxd4
{ Black's usual choice. They can also delay this move and play something like  4...g6  , when  5.Nf3  and a quick O-O completes our kingside development. Black will usually take on d4 at some point, transposing to our main line of the current chapter. }
5. cxd4
{ This position frequently arises via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/2p5/3PP3/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...cxd4  4.cxd4  Nf6  5.Bd3  , when Black has traded the pawns one move earlier. Now Black's mains moves are  5...g6  , and  5...Nc6  − let's have a look. }
5... Nc6
{ Black attacks our unprotected d-pawn. Should we cover or advance it? } 6. Nf3
{ I suggest covering the pawn, but  6.d5  is not a mistake. We gain a lot of space, and Black's knight has to move again. I still prefer  6.Nf3  though. We keep a strong central pawn duo and may still advance one of the pawns later.  Now we need to examine  6...Bg4  , a logical pinning move to increase the pressure on our center. An alternative for Black is  6...g6  , when  7.Nc3  or  7.h3  leads to a position that we examine via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/3B4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...g6  6.Nf3  , the current chapter's main line. }
6... Bg4
{ A natural move, pinning our knight. As a consequence, our d-pawn is now hanging. }
7. Be3
{ Again, I prefer to cover the center and not advance the d-pawn. I think  7.d5  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  Ne5  allows Black some trades and helps them to organize.   How does it continue after  7.Be3  , though? Black needs to decide how to develop their kingside.  A.  7...g6  . I suggest  8.Nbd2  , an idea that we employ in the 5...g6 variation too. Please see the notes to this line about why placing the  knight on d2 is strong here.   B.  7...e6  is a different idea. Black's bishop will be less  active on e7, which gives us more choices. We could play  8.Nc3  or  8.O-O  , for example. We have some advantage due to our strong center. }
