1. e4 c5 2. c3 d6
{ Black goes for  2...d6  , which prepares the attack on our e-pawn  with ...Nf6. Black argues that  2...Nf6  is answered by  3.e5  , so they want to prepare the knight jump by covering  the e5-square. This concept makes sense but does not stop us from building and maintaining the strong pawn duo e4&d4. }
3. d4
{ Easy, that was our idea. Now we'll focus on  3...Nf6  , which attacks our e-pawn. Black also frequently inserts  3...cxd4  4.cxd4  and then plays  4...Nf6  , when  5.Bd3  leads to positions that we'll examine in a moment. }
3... Nf6 { Black attacks our e-pawn, the idea of the previous move. } 4. Bd3
{ We cover our central pawn and get one move closer to kingside castling. This move looks very logical and leads to positions that are simple to play. }
4... cxd4
{ Black's usual choice. They can also delay this move and play something like  4...g6  , when  5.Nf3  and a quick O-O completes our kingside development. Black will usually take on d4 at some point, transposing to our main line of the current chapter. }
5. cxd4
{ This position frequently arises via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/2p5/3PP3/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...cxd4  4.cxd4  Nf6  5.Bd3  , when Black has traded the pawns one move earlier. Now Black's mains moves are  5...g6  , and  5...Nc6  − let's have a look. }
5... g6
{ Black opts for the kingside fianchetto. This setup makes great sense, as the g7-bishop will be aimed at our d4-pawn. Currently, this pawn is undefended and could be a potential target for Black. }
6. Nf3
{ A natural move that protects the d4-pawn and gets us one move closer to kingside castling. }
6... Bg7
{ A very natural move, but Black may also go for  6...Bg4  , pinning our knight. A strong reply is  7.Nbd2!  , anticipating the capture of our knight. More about this idea in a minute. }
7. O-O
{ We castle, as planned. It is worth discussing some subtle points about this position. Black has one viable target, our d4-pawn. We need to be a bit careful about it, as the following sequence shows.   7...O-O  8.Nc3?!  This standard move is not optimal.  8...Bg4!  Attacking the d-pawn by pinning.  9.Be3  Nc6  10.h3?!  Bxf3  11.Qxf3  Nd7!  , when Black has generated a strong attack on our d-pawn.  12.Ne2?  even fails to  12...Nde5!  , winning a pawn for Black! This line is far from the best play by White, but it illustrates Black's basic ideas. How to improve White's play? Let's consider two options for Black.   A.  7...O-O  is the most natural move. Now I suggest investing some time to play  8.h3!  , which stops Black's pinning  idea ...Bg4. After h3 is on the board, we can continue with Nc3 and Be3, and complete our development.   B.  7...Bg4  is possible, setting up the pin before we  play h3 @@StartBracket@@line A@@EndBracket@@. We have a good reply, the move  8.Nbd2  , which allows us to  answer ...Bxf3 with Nxf3, keeping d4 nicely covered.  After  8...O-O  9.h3  Bxf3  10.Nxf3  , our chances are excellent. Our center is stable, and we enjoy the pair of bishops. This leads to the conclusion that we need to either play an  early h3 to stop ...Bg4, or we need to be able to answer ...Bg4 with Nbd2.   Looking back at the previous moves is interesting too.  It is perfectly possible  for us to play  7.h3  or even @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/3B4/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.h3  to prevent  any ...Bg4 ideas.  It is not necessary  though. As long as we can answer ...Bg4 with Nbd2, developing the kingside and castling is just as good.   Conclusion: Black's opening concept does not stop our intention to build a strong center. We have good chances for an advantage based on our excellent central control. It is worth studying the notes to  7.O-O  above.  Black has some ideas to attack our center @@StartBracket@@...Bg4, ...Nc6@@EndBracket@@, and it's instructive to study how to fight them effectively. If you want to learn more about these positions, please study the model gameJ. van Foreest-A. Fedorov }
