1. e4 c5 2. c3 e6
{ Black prepares the move ...d5, an idea similar to the French Defense. It is no surprise that the following lines feature multiple possible transpositions to this opening or its typical structures. }
3. d4
{ The automatic reply, completing our central pawn duo. Now Black only has only one fully satisfactory move,  3...d5  . In practice, you'll frequently meet weaker alternatives though. A common reply is the premature  3...cxd4?!  , which helps our cause by  allowing Nc3 soon.   Are there other serious options? Black sometimes goes for  3...Nc6?  4.d5  , which we cover in our chapter on 2...Nc6.   Passive moves like  3...d6  or  3...b6  are best answered by a natural setup  of Nf3, Bd3, and O-O. }
3... cxd4
{ As always, we are happy about this trade. After our natural reply, we'll gain the c3-square for our knight. }
4. cxd4
{ Now, Black's best move is  4...d5  , but you'll also encounter some worse alternatives. One is  4...Nc6?  5.d5  , which we examine in the chapter on @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  Nc6  . White is much better.   I also found some games featuring  4...Bb4+  and  4...Nf6  . These moves are best answered by developing  with Nc3 and Bd3, preparing kingside castling. }
4... d5
{ This is best. Black needs a pawn on a central square, attacking our e-pawn. We have reached an interesting moment because the position is very similar to a French Defense: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  , when we need to decide about our e-pawn too. With c-pawns on the board, in the French, I recommend  3.exd5  exd5  4.c4  , putting pressure  on d5. This concept doesn't work here in the Sicilian for obvious reasons: the c-pawns are already traded. What to do? }
5. e5
{ I suggest advancing the pawn. Let's discuss why.   A. Compared to the French Advance @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  @@EndBracket@@, the c-pawns are gone. In the French, you could reach the position via  3...c5  4.c3  cxd4?!  5.cxd4  , but it is a dubious line. Without the c-pawns, we can develop our queen's knight to its most active  square on c3, which is impossible if Black delays/omits the trade. For example, Black can wait until White has chosen a worse square @@StartBracket@@like a3@@EndBracket@@ and only trade on d4 if desired. After the premature trade of the c-pawns, we always have the excellent c3-square for our knight to enter the game.   B. While option A is objectively strong, the alternatives don't convince. Going for  5.exd5  exd5  is toothless, as the position is completely symmetrical. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  dxe4  , Black is fine too.   An additional note: I considered recommending  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  , but I thought these lines are complex and French players feel more at home in these positions. Therefore, I suggest a different, less 'French-looking' approach. I am happy to recommend this  improved version  of the French Advance. Black started with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  , not  1...e6  − they will likely not know these positions well. It gives us a good opportunity to play this pawn structure under particularly favorable conditions. }
5... Nc6
{ The most popular and best move. Black wants to put pressure on our d-pawn. They can increase it with a later ...Qb6 or ...Ne7-f5. Our goal is to keep this pawn safely protected, and seek to exploit our advantage in space. }
6. Nf3
{ The best square for our knight. We cover d4 and prepare kingside castling. Let's have a quick look at some possible ideas.   A.  6...Qb6  looks sensible, to put more pressure  on d4. Now  7.Nc3  is a good reply. It not only develops a piece but will often be useful to start an attack on the queenside. After  7...Bd7  8.a3!  ,  @@StartBracket@@preparing Na4@@EndBracket@@  8...Rc8  9.Na4  Qc7  10.Bd3  , we are much better.  A later b2-b4 gives us an excellent game on the queenside.   B.  6...Nge7  7.Nc3  Nf5  is an interesting line. Black wants to  play ...Qb6 next, attacking our pawn even more. A strong reply is similar to line A,  8.a3!  , so that  8...Qb6  9.Na4!  is possible, sending the queen to a passive square. We needed to play the  move a3 to enable  9...Qa5?  10.b4  , rendering Black's concept a complete failure. Finally, a look at a popular but bad move.   C.  6...Bb4+?  7.Nc3  Nge7  is frequently seen below the master level. The fundamental problem of Black's concept is the bishop's placement  on b4. Taking our knight looks unattractive... so what is the bishop doing on b4? An additional problem: the bishop may be a useful defender of the kingside. After  8.Bd3  O-O??  , we see a striking example, as  9.Bxh7+!  is already 'Lights Out!' for Black. The 'Greek Gift', as we call it, is a common attacking idea in French structures. If you don't know this idea, don't worry. There is plenty of material on it on Chessable.  We can conclude that this line offers White good chances. A good illustration of the key ideas is the game M.Socko-P.Ofstad }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Alapin 2.c3 e6"]
[Black "Alapin 2.c3 e6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 e6
{ Black prepares the move ...d5, an idea similar to the French Defense. It is no surprise that the following lines feature multiple possible transpositions to this opening or its typical structures. }
3. d4
{ The automatic reply, completing our central pawn duo. Now Black only has only one fully satisfactory move,  3...d5  . In practice, you'll frequently meet weaker alternatives though. A common reply is the premature  3...cxd4?!  , which helps our cause by  allowing Nc3 soon.   Are there other serious options? Black sometimes goes for  3...Nc6?  4.d5  , which we cover in our chapter on 2...Nc6.   Passive moves like  3...d6  or  3...b6  are best answered by a natural setup  of Nf3, Bd3, and O-O. }
3... d5
{ This looks like Black's best option. Now we have a crucial choice between advancing our e-pawn or capturing Black's d-pawn. }
4. exd5
{ This move aligns with our repertoire choice against the French Defense. After  4.e5  , we would transpose to the main line of the French Advance Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  c5  4.c3  , which is not part of our repertoire. I considered this line but felt that Black usually feels more at home in these structures when they opt for the French.   Instead of transposing out of our repertoire, I suggest playing  4.exd5  , when  4...Qxd5  would again lead to a transposition. This position is covered via  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  e6  , which is a more common way to get to the same situation. }
4... exd5
{ Black takes with the pawn and avoids the transposition after the queen move. As mentioned,  4...Qxd5  is covered via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c3  d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  e6  in a different chapter.   What happens after  4...exd5  , though? First, it's fun to compare this position to the following: with White, we play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  exd5  4.c4  , when  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  c6  is a common continuation. Here, in the Sicilian, we switch sides but enjoy an extra tempo! This extra tempo is important because the position is wide open. We want to make use of it by developing quickly. The best way to do it is playing our knight  to f3 and our bishop to b5, trying to castle as fast as possible. }
5. Bb5+
{ I like this a bit more than  5.Nf3  , but both moves will likely lead to the same positions − we want to play both anyway. }
5... Nc6
{ Or  5...Bd7  6.Bxd7+  Nxd7  7.Nf3  followed by O-O. We develop quickly and will be the first to operate on the e-file. }
6. Nf3
{ No surprises, but good moves. We want to castle next and get our rook into the game. Black's king is still on e8, and the e-file is wide open! This position is only slightly better for White if Black plays perfectly. In practice, this proves difficult.   A.  6...Bd6!  is best, but it is not an obvious move. The idea is that Black can block a check on the e-file with the  move ...Nge7. After  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.O-O  Nge7  , Black's king is safe for the moment. Black' knight  on e7 is not ideally placed, but the king's safety is more important. We have a small advantage in this position, trying to exploit the isolated d-pawn. The next step is Nb1-d2-b3, increasing our control of the d4-square. We want to trade as many minor pieces as possible, as each trade makes the isolated pawn more vulnerable in an endgame.   B.  6...Nf6  is less reliable for Black. After  7.O-O  Be7  8.dxc5  Bxc5  , we can play  9.Bg5  , which shows a  drawback of ...Nf6: the pin is annoying for Black. We'll follow a similar strategy as described in A  above @@StartBracket@@Nb1-d2-b3 next@@EndBracket@@ and have good chances for an advantage.   Conclusion: If they continue with optimal play, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  is a reasonable choice for Black. In practice, however, Black often invites a transposition to a worse version of the French, which we happily accept. We have a nice advantage and good attacking chances after  3.d4  cxd4?!  4.cxd4  d5  5.e5!  A better option for Black is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/3PP3/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d5  , which leads to a different pawn structure after  4.exd5  exd5  , and usually features an IQP on our opponent's side. We can castle quickly and are quicker on the e-file, which makes it easier for us to play. }
