[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Alapin 2.c3 d5"]
[Black "Alapin 2.c3 d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5
{ On the master level, Black usually chooses between two replies to the Alapin:  2...Nf6  and  2...d5  , which we examine in the current chapter. Both moves share a common concept: Black attacks our e-pawn immediately and forces our pawn to capture or advance.   We don't get the opportunity to realize our main strategic goal, which is to establish a perfect pawn duo in the center. Lines like  2...d6?!  3.d4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  3.d4  allow us to build the desired pawn formation. }
3. exd5
{ Taking the pawn is best. We open the position and have good chances to gain a bit of time on Black's queen after their recapture. }
3... Qxd5
{ Moving the queen early in the opening is often a dubious idea. The queen, being the most valuable piece, can get chased around by lesser pieces. In this concrete case, Black's play is justified if they continue in the correct way.   The key point to understand is that as long as our pawn is on c3, the queen can't be attacked by the move Nc3. This is a key difference to the Scandinavian @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  , when  3.Nc3  develops the knight with a tempo gain. In our Alapin line, Black should avoid this scenario. Let's look at this point again after our natural reply. }
4. d4
{ Now we need to consider three basic scenarios.   A.  4...cxd4?!  is very popular below master-level, but a conceptual mistake. After  5.cxd4  , we are ready to  play Nc3 with a gain of time.   B. Black correctly avoids the trade and aims for a setup with an active development of the c8-bishop, for example, after  4...Nc6  5.Nf3  Bg4  or @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pq4/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  Bg4  .   C. Black avoids the trade and aims for quick kingside development with  4...e6  or  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  e6  ,  keeping the bishop on c8 for a while. Let's examine these three concepts. }
4... Nc6
{ We'll have a closer look at this move, to illustrate Black's plan to keep the central pawn tension and develop the c8-bishop actively after our natural reply. The same concept can also be applied by starting  4...Nf6  , when  5.Nf3  Bg4  6.Be2  is similar to the line we are about to examine. }
5. Nf3 { We cover our d-pawn and get one move closer to kingside castling. }
5... Bg4
{ Black pins our knight and increases the pressure on the d-pawn, a common idea. It is not the only one though. Let's have a quick look at alternatives, which are mostly just transposing to position types we cover via a different move order.   A.  5...cxd4?!  6.cxd4  leads to lines we examine via 4...cxd4 in the current chapter.   B.  5...Nf6  is a good move that does not yet commit the placement of  the c8-bishop. We simply play  6.Be2  , and castle kingside next. If Black plays  6...Bg4  , we'll get to positions that arise via 5...Bg4; if they play an early  6...e6  , we'll transpose to lines that we check via 4...e6 −  we play the natural moves Nf3, Be2 and O-O in all cases. }
6. Be2
{ We break the pin and are ready to castle kingside next. Now Black again has the choice between taking on d4 or continuing their development.   After  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  , we reach a position that we examine via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pq4/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...cxd4  5.cxd4  Nc6  6.Nf3  Bg4  7.Be2  in the current chapter.  Black may also play @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/2pq4/3P2b1/2P2N2/PP2BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  or  6...Nf6  , keeping the pawn tension. In this case, we have the comfortable choice between simply castling to secure our king, or starting a direct action in the center.  An interesting line to illustrate this idea is  6...e6  7.h3  Bh5  8.c4  , which attacks the black queen and intends  to play d4-d5 next, gaining even more time with an attack on the knight. This is a promising idea, but the simple  7.O-O  is no mistake, of course. We get to complete our development  with Be3 and possibly Na3 next. }
