[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Alapin 2.c3 d5"]
[Black "Alapin 2.c3 d5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5
{ On the master level, Black usually chooses between two replies to the Alapin:  2...Nf6  and  2...d5  , which we examine in the current chapter. Both moves share a common concept: Black attacks our e-pawn immediately and forces our pawn to capture or advance.   We don't get the opportunity to realize our main strategic goal, which is to establish a perfect pawn duo in the center. Lines like  2...d6?!  3.d4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  3.d4  allow us to build the desired pawn formation. }
3. exd5
{ Taking the pawn is best. We open the position and have good chances to gain a bit of time on Black's queen after their recapture. }
3... Qxd5
{ Moving the queen early in the opening is often a dubious idea. The queen, being the most valuable piece, can get chased around by lesser pieces. In this concrete case, Black's play is justified if they continue in the correct way.   The key point to understand is that as long as our pawn is on c3, the queen can't be attacked by the move Nc3. This is a key difference to the Scandinavian @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  , when  3.Nc3  develops the knight with a tempo gain. In our Alapin line, Black should avoid this scenario. Let's look at this point again after our natural reply. }
4. d4
{ Now we need to consider three basic scenarios.   A.  4...cxd4?!  is very popular below master-level, but a conceptual mistake. After  5.cxd4  , we are ready to  play Nc3 with a gain of time.   B. Black correctly avoids the trade and aims for a setup with an active development of the c8-bishop, for example, after  4...Nc6  5.Nf3  Bg4  or @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pq4/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  Bg4  .   C. Black avoids the trade and aims for quick kingside development with  4...e6  or  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  e6  ,  keeping the bishop on c8 for a while. Let's examine these three concepts. }
4... e6
{ Black locks in their c8-bishop, which looks a bit passive. Their setup has an upside, though: Black emphasizes kingside development and usually manages to castle quickly.   I have chosen the  4...e6  move order to show this approach for Black, but they can also start with a knight move and then play the pawn  to e6. For example,  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  e6  or @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pq4/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  5.Nf3  Nf6  6.Be2  e6  are common sequences. It's all easy for us to handle,  as we'll play Nf3, Be2, and O-O anyway. }
5. Nf3 { We get closer to castling by playing Nf3 and Be2 next. } 5... Nf6 6.
Be2
{ I recommend sticking with this bishop development. We usually place the bishop on e2 in this chapter, often as a more or less forced reply to ...Bg4.   In the current position, there is no pin on our knight, which gives us more options. It is perfectly possible to go for  6.Bd3  ,  6.Be3  , or the interesting  6.Na3  @@StartBracket@@intending Nb5@@EndBracket@@, but having a universal setup based on Be2 cuts down our memory load immensely. }
6... Nc6
{ The most natural development scheme for Black is ...Nc6, ...Be7, then castling. It doesn't matter if they start with the knight or bishop move. }
7. O-O
{ Our king is safe now, let's talk further plans. Black has avoided the trade of c-pawns so far. They could have inserted ...cxd4 at any given moment, but we'd be happy about it. As discussed before, the trade gives us the option Nc3, gaining an important tempo for our development. Let's have a look at some sample moves.   A logical way to continue is  7...Be7  8.Be3  , when we threaten to capture the c-pawn. Black can't ignore it, as  8...O-O?  9.dxc5  shows. Black has nothing better than @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/pp2bppp/2n1pn2/2pq4/3P4/2P1BN2/PP2BPPP/RN1Q1RK1 b kq - 7 8@@EndFEN@@  8...cxd4  9.cxd4  O-O  10.Nc3  , which finally wins the desired tempo. An interesting idea worth noting is  10...Qd8  11.Ne5  ,  intending Bf3 next. Our pieces occupy powerful central posts in this setup. }
