[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Alapin 2.c3 d5"]
[Black "Alapin 2.c3 d5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5
{ On the master level, Black usually chooses between two replies to the Alapin:  2...Nf6  and  2...d5  , which we examine in the current chapter. Both moves share a common concept: Black attacks our e-pawn immediately and forces our pawn to capture or advance.   We don't get the opportunity to realize our main strategic goal, which is to establish a perfect pawn duo in the center. Lines like  2...d6?!  3.d4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  3.d4  allow us to build the desired pawn formation. }
3. exd5
{ Taking the pawn is best. We open the position and have good chances to gain a bit of time on Black's queen after their recapture. }
3... Qxd5
{ Moving the queen early in the opening is often a dubious idea. The queen, being the most valuable piece, can get chased around by lesser pieces. In this concrete case, Black's play is justified if they continue in the correct way.   The key point to understand is that as long as our pawn is on c3, the queen can't be attacked by the move Nc3. This is a key difference to the Scandinavian @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  , when  3.Nc3  develops the knight with a tempo gain. In our Alapin line, Black should avoid this scenario. Let's look at this point again after our natural reply. }
4. d4
{ Now we need to consider three basic scenarios.   A.  4...cxd4?!  is very popular below master-level, but a conceptual mistake. After  5.cxd4  , we are ready to  play Nc3 with a gain of time.   B. Black correctly avoids the trade and aims for a setup with an active development of the c8-bishop, for example, after  4...Nc6  5.Nf3  Bg4  or @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pq4/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  Bg4  .   C. Black avoids the trade and aims for quick kingside development with  4...e6  or  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  e6  ,  keeping the bishop on c8 for a while. Let's examine these three concepts. }
4... cxd4
{ We are happy to see this move, as after  5.cxd4  , we are ready to attack Black's queen  with Nc3, gaining a valuable tempo for our development. }
5. cxd4 { Now we are ready to play Nc3, developing with tempo. } 5... Nc6
{ Black attacks our d-pawn, a very logical and popular move. Does Black have a good alternative?   You'll also meet  5...Nf6  6.Nc3  , when Black has a choice of various queen moves. Most popular is  6...Qd8  , when a normal development move like  6.Bc4  gives us some advantage. It is interesting to compare this position to the Caro-Kann, as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.c4  Nf6  5.Nc3  dxc4?!  6.Bxc4  may lead to the same position. It pays off to follow similar concepts across different openings, as you reach familiar structures. }
6. Nf3
{ We need to cover our pawn.  6.Nc3?  Qxd4  drops our most important pawn. }
6... Bg4
{ The most active and most popular move for Black. There are some, mostly bad, alternatives.   A.  6...Nf6?  7.Nc3  Qd8  8.d5  leads to a disaster, as Black needs to return their  knight to b8. We gain too much time and get an attack for free.   B.  6...e6  is a better move, but  7.Nc3  is still nice for White. We discuss a similar setup via @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pq4/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e6  , which is more precise. Black should delay or omit the  trade on d4. }
7. Be2
{ We need to break the pin first. After  7.Nc3  Bxf3!  the game gets very sharp and hard to assess.   We should play  7.Be2  , also for an additional reason. Black may play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  Nc6  5.Nf3  Bg4  , when  6.Be2  cxd4  7.cxd4  leads to the same position.   Now, after  7.Be2  , Black's best move is not so obvious and often avoided below master-level. If you think about the position for a while, you'll see the logic of  7...e6!  , as it anticipates White's idea of  playing Nc3, followed by d4-d5 to attack Black's knight and gain more time. Let's illustrate these ideas.   After  7...e6  8.Nc3  , Black still has to be precise. They often go for  8...Bb4  9.O-O  Bxc3?  10.bxc3  , which is excellent for White due to the strong bishop pair. Much better is @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/3q4/3P2b1/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qa5  9.O-O  Nf6  10.h3  Bh5  11.Be3  , when chances are about equal. We have ideas based  on Qb3, attacking the b7-pawn, but Black's position makes a solid impression.   We now know that  7...e6  is Black's best move,  but what about taking on f3? }
7... Bxf3 { A bad move, but the worst is yet to come... } 8. Bxf3
{ Of course, we played Be2 to enable this move. Now Black's only option is retreating the queen, but we have a large advantage in any case.   After  8...Qd6  9.d5  Ne5  10.O-O  , we have a great position. Black is far behind in development and we have easy attacking ideas  like Nc3-b5, Bf4, and Re1. These natural development moves will put Black under huge pressure. Black still needs multiple moves to castle kingside. }
8... Qxd4
{ Black had to retreat the queen, but I wanted to show why grabbing the pawn doesn't work. }
9. Bxc6+ { We take the queen's sole defender with check and win on the spot. }
9... bxc6 10. Qxd4
{ This sequence has happened in tens of thousands of games! It's just a matter of time until you'll get it on the board, as Black's moves are fairly natural and the tactical point is easy to miss in faster time controls.   Conclusion: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d5  is one of the best replies to the Alapin, but Black needs to know more than that. After the  trade on d4, we gain some time on Black's queen, and they need to play precisely because they are slightly behind in development. Our play is fairly easy. We have a standard way to develop,  based on Nf3, Be2, and a quick O-O.   After  2...d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  , Black will usually trade  on d4 at some point, often immediately on the fourth move. The resulting pawn structure, the IQP @@StartBracket@@Isolated Queen's Pawn@@EndBracket@@ is a common guest in our repertoire. In exchange for a potential weakness of the d-pawn, we can develop our pieces to active squares and often grab the initiative. In most cases, we'll win a tempo on Black's queen by playing Nc3 − unless Black goes for the main line of the chapter and even blunders the queen. :-@@EndBracket@@ }
