[White "14) Alapin 2.c3 Nf6"]
[Black "Alapin 2.c3 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6
{ Black attacks our e-pawn with their knight, forcing the pawn forward. On the master level, this is considered to be a top choice for Black, on par with  2...d5  , the other way to attack our pawn. }
3. e5
{ It makes no sense to protect the e-pawn with a passive move − advancing it with a gain of time is much better. }
3... Nd5
{ Black occupies this nice central post with their knight. Black's main idea behind 2...Nf6 is to lure our pawns forward and then attack them. Black will often play moves like ...Nc6 or ...d5, soon attacking our advanced pawn.  Our idea is simple: we want to play our d-pawn to d4 and develop the kingside by playing Nf3, Bc4 and finally, castle. This logical concept works well against various setups that Black may try. }
4. d4
{ I suggest starting with the pawn move, but playing  4.Nf3  first is fine too. You may combine the  moves d4, Nf3, and Bc4 in various ways. The difference between these orders is minor. As we usually start with the pawn move in other lines of the Alapin, I suggest sticking to this approach here as well. }
4... cxd4
{ An almost automatic reply. Black rarely plays a move like  4...d6  , when I suggest continuing with our normal development plan  of Nf3 and Bc4. After Black's capture on d4, we have a good choice between the simple pawn recapture and the move I suggest − developing the knight first. }
5. Nf3
{ There is nothing wrong about  5.cxd4  ,  but developing our knight first gives us some additional options. Black can't prevent cxd4 anyway, and maybe they overlook  5.Nf3  dxc3??  6.Qxd5  , donating a knight to our good cause. :-@@EndBracket@@   Now Black usually plays  5...Nc6  ,  5...d6  or  5...e6  − these moves are often combined over the next moves, so it might not matter which one they play first. We'll have a look at the most popular continuations  5...Nc6  and  5...e6  now. In all cases, we'll regain the pawn  with cxd4 and develop our bishop to c4. }
5... e6 { A sensible move, as Black wants to get closer to kingside castling. }
6. cxd4 d6
{ This is Black's most popular choice, attacking the e5-pawn. This position may also arise via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/8/3nP3/3p4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  6.cxd4  e6  , of course.   Black has alternatives to  6...d6  , but they don't change our plans.  We want to develop our bishop to c4 and castle kingside. }
7. Bc4
{ The best development option for our bishop. The move  7.Bd3  is less precise because Black has  7...dxe5  8.dxe5  Nb4  , when we need to move the bishop again and allow a queen trade. These trades only help Black, as they have less space.   We should keep more pieces on the board, as the advanced e-pawn might help us to generate an attack on the kingside. Black's knight is nicely placed on d5, but it no longer defends the kingside. After castling kingside first, a common idea for White is to activate the queen via Qd1-e2-e4 to the kingside. }
