4. d4
{ I suggest starting with the pawn move, but playing  4.Nf3  first is fine too. You may combine the  moves d4, Nf3, and Bc4 in various ways. The difference between these orders is minor. As we usually start with the pawn move in other lines of the Alapin, I suggest sticking to this approach here as well. }
4... cxd4
{ An almost automatic reply. Black rarely plays a move like  4...d6  , when I suggest continuing with our normal development plan  of Nf3 and Bc4. After Black's capture on d4, we have a good choice between the simple pawn recapture and the move I suggest − developing the knight first. }
5. Nf3
{ There is nothing wrong about  5.cxd4  ,  but developing our knight first gives us some additional options. Black can't prevent cxd4 anyway, and maybe they overlook  5.Nf3  dxc3??  6.Qxd5  , donating a knight to our good cause. :-@@EndBracket@@   Now Black usually plays  5...Nc6  ,  5...d6  or  5...e6  − these moves are often combined over the next moves, so it might not matter which one they play first. We'll have a look at the most popular continuations  5...Nc6  and  5...e6  now. In all cases, we'll regain the pawn  with cxd4 and develop our bishop to c4. }
5... Nc6
{ Developing the knight is a very natural and logical move. Black opts for this most of the time. }
6. cxd4
{ I suggest this simple capture to restore material equality. White has an interesting alternative here though.   A popular choice is the more complicated  6.Bc4  , which will often involve a pawn sacrifice.  Simply taking on d4, our repertoire move, is easier to play and just as good.   Black has to decide about their central pawn formation now. They often play  6...e6  , which leads to positions quite similar to 5...e6. We'll play  7.Bc4  to develop and castle kingside next. We'll now check @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1ppppp/2n5/3nP3/3P4/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d6  , which might lead to a different scenario. }
6... d6
{ Attacking our e-pawn makes a lot of sense, but Black delays kingside development for a while. Our answer is easy, we always develop our bishop to c4 in the current chapter. }
7. Bc4
{ Again, our natural bishop post in this chapter. We get one move closer to kingside castling and attack Black's knight in the process. Black has some possible options now. Let's have a quick look.   A.  7...Nb6  forces a decision. I suggest  8.Bb5  , pinning Black's knight. A common continuation is  8...dxe5  9.Nxe5  Bd7  10.Nxd7  Qxd7  11.O-O  , when chances are about equal. We have gained the bishop pair, but lost a bit of time in the process.   B.  7...e6  leads to positions that we often reach via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/8/3nP3/3p4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  .   C.  7...dxe5  is rare, but an interesting line. We should answer with the aggressive  8.Bxd5  Qxd5  9.Nc3  Qd6  10.d5  , which gains a lot of time and is tough to play for Black.  Conclusion: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  is a main line on the master level for a good reason. The resulting positions are interesting to play for both sides and give Black good chances to equalize the game.   Our approach against it is quite simple. We play the natural moves d4, Nf3, and Bc4, getting ready for kingside castling. We have established a pawn on e5, which gives us an advantage in space, while Black has a strong square for their knight. Black has a range of options on how to place their central pawns, but our play is quite similar in all cases and follows basic opening principles. }
