[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) French/Caro-Kann − Introduction & Overview"]
[Black "French/Caro-Kann − Introduction & Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Black's most popular replies against  1.e4  are  1...e5  and  1...c5  . These moves share a common idea: controlling  the d4-square, thus making it more difficult for White to achieve the dream pawn duo of e4&d4.  In the next two chapters, we will examine two defenses that follow a different concept.  The French  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  , and the Caro-Kann  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  , allow us to build the pawn center,  but Black's d5-pawn attacks our e-pawn. In both cases, we must decide how to react to this attack. I suggest the same approach against the French and the Caro: trading on d5, followed by the move c2-c4 to put pressure on Black's d5-pawn.   Let's have a look at the moves:  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  exd5  4.c4  and  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.c4  . In both cases, we open the game and make it easy for us to develop our pieces.  Our knights will be well-placed on their natural squares c3 and f3. In most cases, we will play Bd3 and O-O quickly, securing our king.  The open character of the position, with an early pawn tension in the center @@StartBracket@@c4, attacking d5@@EndBracket@@, will often yield tactical complications. Our lines against the French and Caro usually lead to a common pawn structure, the Isolated Queen's Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@. A sample line is  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  exd5  4.c4  dxc4  5.Bxc4  , when our d-pawn is 'isolated'. Isolated means that a pawn on an adjacent file can't support the pawn. An isolated pawn has upsides and downsides.  IQP upsides: The huge upside is − these positions feature active pieces and therefore are rich in tactics and attacks. We never have to ask ourselves a question like 'How do I develop this bishop?'. It's a wide open position with active spots for our pieces.  IQP downsides: The downside of an isolated pawn is that it can't be covered by a pawn anymore. Such a pawn can be a weakness and target for our opponent, especially in an endgame. Generally, we should keep as many pieces on the board as possible and avoid trades.  This pawn structure also features in our repertoire suggestion against the Sicilian, when  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  cxd4  5.cxd4  is one way to get to the same pawn structure. There are even some full transpositions between the chapters.  Let's explore how to fight the French and the Caro-Kann! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) French 1.e4 e6"]
[Black "French 1.e4 e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense. Black wants to answer  2.d4  with  2...d5  , attacking our e-pawn. }
2. d4 d5
{ That's the idea of 1...e6: Black establishes a pawn on d5 and now attacks our e-pawn. The move  2...d5  is by far the most popular and best move, but you'll sometimes meet different ideas.   A move worth mentioning is  2...c5  when we have a good choice. The reply  3.c3  is simple and good, leading to a position we can reach via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  e6  3.d4  − objectively, even better is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/2p5/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d5  , gaining space in the center of the board. Black's bishops are passive, while we can easily develop and prepare kingside castling  with Nf3, Be2 or Bd3 and finally O-O.   Other second moves don't require any specific knowledge, as they are too passive. Against something like  2...d6  or  2...b6  , we should develop  with Nf3, Bd3 and O-O, and enjoy our superior central control and development. }
3. exd5
{ The Exchange Variation is a surprising choice, as it is usually believed to be harmless for Black. We have an active idea in mind though. }
3... exd5
{ You rarely meet  3...Qxd5  , a much inferior relative of the Scandi. We'll happily play  4.Nc3  to gain time, while Black might wonder  why ... e6 is on the board, leaving the c8-bishop in a sad state. }
4. c4
{ This is the way to spice up the game. We want to attack Black's d-pawn and open the position as much as possible.   We'll check  4...Nf6  and  4...dxc4  now. You'll also frequently meet  4...c6  , but we'll cover this setup via  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  c6  , which is a common alternative move order.  A great feature of our setup is that we develop our pieces to active  and logical posts: the knights go to c3 and f3, and we place the bishop on d3 and castle kingside. }
4... dxc4
{ Black immediately releases the central tension. We love to see this move, as we manage to recapture on c4 without having moved the bishop first. It's more attractive for Black to wait for Bd3 and only then capture the c-pawn. }
5. Bxc4
{ An easy move for us. Now we see a key point of the 4.c4 idea: our bishop is well-placed on c4, building up pressure against the f7-pawn. This pawn is vulnerable, as it is only covered by the king. }
5... Nf6
{ Black's alternative is  5...Bb4+  6.Nc3  , when we will likely reach a version of this chapter's main line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  Bb4  6.Nf3  O-O  7.Bd3  , when Black often captures  on c4 soon. In this case, our bishop takes two moves to regain the pawn, while here, we have saved a tempo by capturing in one go. We win a bit of time in a wide-open position, which renders the whole  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...dxc4  line dubious.   Back to  5...Nf6  − what now? Nothing is wrong with a healthy development like  6.Nf3  or  6.Nc3  , but I suggest a more aggressive move. }
6. Qb3
{ Going for the f7-weakness. Black has no simple way to cover it; the only option is a queen move. }
6... Qe7+
{ The only good move because of the ... Qb4+ idea. Let's continue to see what I am talking about. }
7. Ne2
{ We block the check and are ready to castle now. Now Black needs to untangle their kingside development.   The only good move is  7...Qb4+  8.Nbc3  Qxb3  9.Bxb3  , when we have an advantage, but Black's position is acceptable. We are much better developed and are faster to play on the open e-file. Black has to go for the queen check, as otherwise,  we manage O-O, and Re1 will lead to awkward moments for the black queen. }
