{ A common move is  6...Bb4  , leading to positions that we examine via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/5n2/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bb4  , the current chapter's main line. }
7. Bd3 { Getting ready for castling. } 7... O-O 8. O-O
{ A good moment to take stock. Both sides have completed the kingside development and can be satisfied with the opening outcome. Our chances are slightly better, as we have more active pieces − compare Nc3/Bd3 with their counterparts. Let's look at some more moves to illustrate the play.   Black often goes for  8...Bg4  , when I suggest  9.Re1  dxc4  10.Bxc4  , which looks logical. A good idea to know is  10...Nbd7  11.h3  Bh5  and now  12.g4!  Bg6  13.Ne5  , when  we threaten f2-f4-f5, attacking Black's bishop. The pawn advance on the kingside involves some risk for us, but Black is under strong pressure. }
