[White "17) Caro-Kann 1.e4 c6"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 1.e4 c6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann follows a similar idea as the French Defense. Black intends to challenge our e-pawn and prepares the strike ...d7-d5 on the next move. }
2. d4
{ We happily accept the invitation to build the full center, even if it is just a temporary achievement. Black almost always continues with the logical move  2...d5  , but you'll also meet other 'small' moves like  2...d6  ,  2...g6  , or similarly passive options. In these cases, we don't face immediate pressure on our center @@StartBracket@@compared to  2...d5  , when our e-pawn is attacked@@EndBracket@@ and can continue with our kingside development.  A setup based on Nf3, Bd3/Be2 and O-O comes to mind. }
2... d5
{ Now we need to decide what to do about our e-pawn. We can move the pawn or cover it. I suggest an aggressive option, the so-called Panov Attack. It is the variation against the Caro-Kann that leads to the most open positions, similar to positions that we reach in other lines of our repertoire. }
3. exd5 { The first step to the Panov − we trade on d5. } 3... cxd5 4. c4
{ After this aggressive pawn push we have reached the Panov. White gets the c-pawn involved and increases the pressure on Black's d-pawn. How do we continue on the next moves? Our general plan is to develop quickly and castle kingside. The setup Nc3, Nf3, Bd3 and O-O comes to mind.  An important idea to remember: If Black tries to develop their c8-bishop actively, we often have the strong reply Qb3, attacking both d5 and b7. We'll see more of this idea in the variations we will examine in a moment.   How does Black continue now? The best and most flexible move is  4...Nf6  , which we will focus on. A different option is  4...dxc4  5.Bxc4  , which gives us the welcome opportunity  to place our bishop on the attractive c4-square. }
4... dxc4
{ We are happy to see this move, as it allows us an active development of our bishop to c4 in one move. }
5. Bxc4 { OK, that was an easy move. } 5... Nf6
{ Black gets one move closer to castling. } 6. Nf3
{ A good alternative is  6.Nc3  , which will usually lead to the same positions.  We want to place our knights on c3 and f3 and castle kingside. The order does not matter that much, but going  6.Nf3  first sets a small trap. }
6... Bg4
{ Pinning our knight looks like an active idea, but this move is still a blunder! Instead, Black should play the modest  6...e6  , when we continue with  7.O-O  and enjoy a comfortable position.  The current chapter's main line is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3p4/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  e6  6.Nf3  Bb4  7.Bd3  ,  when Black usually captures on c4 soon. In this line, we take two moves to place the bishop on c4, where after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3p4/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...dxc4  5.Bxc4  , we only needed one move to reach the same situation. We are a full tempo up on a main line, an excellent opening result. }
7. Bxf7+
{ Boom! Always look for tactics if your bishop keeps an eye on the vulnerable f7-square. The superficial move 6...Bg4?? invited this tactic, winning a pawn with a fantastic position on top! }
7... Kxf7 8. Ne5+
{ The point of the bishop sacrifice: we regain the piece with interest. Note that the following line even leads to a checkmate:  8...Kg8  9.Nxg4  Nxg4??  10.Qb3+!  and Black has no way to stop the mate! }
