[White "17) Caro-Kann 1.e4 c6"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 1.e4 c6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann follows a similar idea as the French Defense. Black intends to challenge our e-pawn and prepares the strike ...d7-d5 on the next move. }
2. d4
{ We happily accept the invitation to build the full center, even if it is just a temporary achievement. Black almost always continues with the logical move  2...d5  , but you'll also meet other 'small' moves like  2...d6  ,  2...g6  , or similarly passive options. In these cases, we don't face immediate pressure on our center @@StartBracket@@compared to  2...d5  , when our e-pawn is attacked@@EndBracket@@ and can continue with our kingside development.  A setup based on Nf3, Bd3/Be2 and O-O comes to mind. }
2... d5
{ Now we need to decide what to do about our e-pawn. We can move the pawn or cover it. I suggest an aggressive option, the so-called Panov Attack. It is the variation against the Caro-Kann that leads to the most open positions, similar to positions that we reach in other lines of our repertoire. }
3. exd5 { The first step to the Panov − we trade on d5. } 3... cxd5 4. c4
{ After this aggressive pawn push we have reached the Panov. White gets the c-pawn involved and increases the pressure on Black's d-pawn. How do we continue on the next moves? Our general plan is to develop quickly and castle kingside. The setup Nc3, Nf3, Bd3 and O-O comes to mind.  An important idea to remember: If Black tries to develop their c8-bishop actively, we often have the strong reply Qb3, attacking both d5 and b7. We'll see more of this idea in the variations we will examine in a moment.   How does Black continue now? The best and most flexible move is  4...Nf6  , which we will focus on. A different option is  4...dxc4  5.Bxc4  , which gives us the welcome opportunity  to place our bishop on the attractive c4-square. }
4... Nf6
{ Black's most flexible move. The knight develops to its best square and is ready to recapture on d5. There are some alternatives with little independent significance:   A.  4...Nc6  is a rare move. After  5.cxd5  Qxd5  6.Nf3  , we transpose to a position that we usually reach via a different opening − the Alapin Sicilian! The 'Sicilian way' to get here is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  cxd4  5.cxd4  Nc6  6.Nf3  , leading to the same position.  B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3p4/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e6  is a solid move to cover the d-pawn. After  5.Nc3  Nf6  6.Nf3  , we'll reach a position we cover via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/3p4/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  e6  6.Nf3  − hang on. }
5. Nc3
{ Developing this knight first is slightly more precise than  5.Nf3  because we put more pressure on the d-pawn. An instructive line to illustrate this point is  5.Nc3  Bf5?  6.Qb3!  ,  when we attack d5 and b7, winning a pawn!   We'll now focus on Black's two most popular setups:  5...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@still aiming to develop the c8-bishop actively@@EndBracket@@  and  5...e6  , which prioritizes faster kingside development. }
5... Nc6
{ Black develops the knight to the natural square and avoids the move ...e6, which would put the c8-bishop on a passive spot.   The point of  5...Nc6  is aiming for an active bishop development after the common reply  6.Nf3  , when  6...Bg4  is possible. I suggest avoiding this line because we have an alternative that is tricky to handle for Black. }
6. Bg5
{ There is nothing wrong about  6.Nf3  Bg4  7.cxd5  Nxd5  8.Qb3  , but I prefer the bishop move for practical reasons. Black often struggles to find the best defense and will reach positions that they are less familiar with. Our idea is simple:  we threaten to capture the knight and win the d5-pawn. }
6... dxc4
{ We need to check this move. Black often goes for  6...e6  , when we reach positions similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/5n2/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  . What to do after the pawn capture though? }
7. d5
{ This puts Black under a lot of pressure. We immediately start an attack on Black's knight and force a decision.   I want to add that  7.Bxc4  is a good alternative. Black can play  7...Qxd4  8.Qxd4  Nxd4  , but  9.O-O-O!  gives White excellent play for the pawn. Black needs to be cautious in this line too. }
7... Ne5
{ This looks like the most logical move, jumping to the central square. You'll also meet  7...Nb4???  8.Qa4+  , winning the knight! }
8. Qd4
{ This is a crucial move to remember. Now Black either knows the best move or will face an uphill struggle. Let's have an overview.   A.  8...h6!  is the best move, but it's tough to find. After  9.Bf4  Ng6  10.Bxc4  , we reach an interesting position with about equal chances. Our development is much better, but Black can take our bishop and gain the bishop pair.   B.  8...Nd3+?!  is the most popular move, but dubious. After  9.Bxd3  cxd3  10.Qxd3  , we have a serious lead in development.  We play Nf3, O-O and Rfe1 next, starting to put pressure on the e7-pawn. }
