5. Nc3
{ Developing this knight first is slightly more precise than  5.Nf3  because we put more pressure on the d-pawn. An instructive line to illustrate this point is  5.Nc3  Bf5?  6.Qb3!  ,  when we attack d5 and b7, winning a pawn!   We'll now focus on Black's two most popular setups:  5...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@still aiming to develop the c8-bishop actively@@EndBracket@@  and  5...e6  , which prioritizes faster kingside development. }
5... e6
{ Black wants to castle quickly and emphasizes kingside development. This is a solid continuation but less active than  5...Nc6  ,  which still keeps the option of ...Bg4. }
6. Nf3
{ A natural development move. Now Black usually goes for  6...Bb4  , preparing to castle. }
6... Bb4
{ The most popular move and logical. An alternative for Black is  6...Nc6  , when  7.c5  is an interesting reply. We gain space on the queenside and intend to advance our b-pawn later, to create an attack on this side of the board. }
7. Bd3
{ An easy choice, as we want to castle kingside as soon as possible. Let's consider both sides' options after castling. }
7... O-O 8. O-O
{ A good moment to take stock. We have completed our kingside development and secured our king. How does the game continue? Black will usually capture on c4 soon, as they want to create an isolated d-pawn in our camp. This pawn is a potential target to attack, as it can't be protected by another pawn anymore. It is actually difficult for Black to keep the central pawn tension for much longer, as we are ready to play Bg5 and increase the pressure on d5. Let's show some possible ideas.   A.  8...Nc6  9.Bg5  b6?  is an example of an ill-fated attempt to avoid taking  on c4. After  10.cxd5  exd5  11.Bxf6  Qxf6  12.Nxd5  , Black is toast. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p4ppp/1pn2B2/3p4/1b1P4/2NB1N2/PP3PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...gxf6?  12.Nh4  to prepare Qh5 is even worse. This line illustrates why taking on c4 is Black's preferred option.   B.  8...dxc4  9.Bxc4  reaches the Isolated Queen's Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@. We have active posts for our pieces;  moves like Bg5 and placing the rooks on c1 and e1 come to mind. See the game Timofeev-Svidler for more information.   I want to mention two key ideas for White. The first is playing d4-d5 at the right moment. This move can open the center in our favor, using the superior development. A sample line to illustrate this concept is  9...Nc6  10.Bg5  Bd7?  11.d5!  exd5  12.Nxd5  , which gives us a strong attack.  A second idea worth knowing is starting an attack on the kingside. Let's have a look:  9...Nc6  10.Bg5  Be7  11.Rc1  a6  @@StartBracket@@Black plans ...b5 and ...Bb7 to activate the bishop@@EndBracket@@  12.Bb3  Na5  @@StartBracket@@  12...b5?  13.Nxb5!  wins a pawn@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p2bppp/p3pn2/n5B1/3P4/1BN2N2/PP3PPP/2RQ1RK1 w - - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Bc2  b5  and now  14.Qd3  , which creates a 'battery', as we call it.  We threaten Bxf6, followed by Qxh7#!  Conclusion: The Panov Attack against the Caro-Kann is an aggressive weapon that allows us to develop our pieces into active and natural squares. It perfectly aligns with general opening principles and puts Black to the test, as each tempo is relevant. We often reach IQP positions that lead to exciting play and attacks based on our advantage in space. }
