[White "18) Scandinavian 1.e4 d5"]
[Black "Scandinavian 1.e4 d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandi! This opening is surprisingly popular below the master level, maybe due to the efforts of popular Chessable co-founder John Bartholomew. Black immediately strikes in the center but will lose some time after the usual continuation  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  , when Black needs to move their queen a second time. This makes it 2 queen moves out of 3 at the start of the game! This can't be ideal, so it's no surprise that White has good chances for a plus against the Scandi.  There is a catch though. Playing White, you don't meet this opening frequently. On the other hand, Black might play it every time against 1.e4, giving our opponent a large edge in terms of experience. Therefore it makes a lot of sense to take the opening seriously and learn a good reply to the Scandi. The first step is simple: we take the pawn. }
2. exd5
{ The best move by far. Black needs to invest some time to regain the pawn. Now we will focus on  2...Qxd5  , Black's most popular reply. You also meet  2...Nf6  , which we will check briefly too. }
2... Nf6
{ Black wants to avoid multiple queen moves and tries to regain the pawn more conveniently with their knight. I suggest a simple reply that will transpose to other variations that are part of our repertoire. }
3. c4
{ White has many good alternatives here, like  3.d4  ,  3.Nf3  or  3.Bb5+  , which all promise an advantage. My recommendation will save us some work, as Black's only reasonable replies to  3.c4  will transpose to the Caro-Kann or the French Defense. How does that work? }
3... c6
{ With 3.c4, we had covered the d-pawn. Black needs to eliminate the d5-pawn, as it severely hampers development. The way to go for Black is playing  3...c6  or the similar  3...e6  , trying to capitalize on White's excessive greed. Black hopes for  3...c6  4.dxc6?  Nxc6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3P4/2P5/8/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.dxe6?!  Bxe6  , when they have a great development for the sacrificed pawn. Instead, we must avoid this scenario and focus on our development. }
4. d4
{ We have to avoid the pawn grab and instead follow basic opening principles: occupy the center and emphasize your development. The same approach works well after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3P4/2P5/8/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq c3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  , when  4.d4  exd5  5.Nc3  directly transposes to our lines against the French Defense. }
4... cxd5 { Black regains the pawn. } 5. Nc3
{ And we have transposed to the Panov Attack, our choice against the Caro-Kann. In the Caro, we'd reach the same position via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.c4  Nf6  5.Nc3  − please check the chapter on the Caro-Kann for more information. }
