[White "18) Scandinavian 1.e4 d5"]
[Black "Scandinavian 1.e4 d5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandi! This opening is surprisingly popular below the master level, maybe due to the efforts of popular Chessable co-founder John Bartholomew. Black immediately strikes in the center but will lose some time after the usual continuation  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  , when Black needs to move their queen a second time. This makes it 2 queen moves out of 3 at the start of the game! This can't be ideal, so it's no surprise that White has good chances for a plus against the Scandi.  There is a catch though. Playing White, you don't meet this opening frequently. On the other hand, Black might play it every time against 1.e4, giving our opponent a large edge in terms of experience. Therefore it makes a lot of sense to take the opening seriously and learn a good reply to the Scandi. The first step is simple: we take the pawn. }
2. exd5
{ The best move by far. Black needs to invest some time to regain the pawn. Now we will focus on  2...Qxd5  , Black's most popular reply. You also meet  2...Nf6  , which we will check briefly too. }
2... Qxd5
{ Black has 'developed' the queen, but it is a target for our knight. } 3. Nc3
{ Here we go! We get our piece into the game while Black is forced to move the queen a second time. Where does it go? We'll look at the most popular options:  3...Qa5  @@StartBracket@@active@@EndBracket@@, and  3...Qd8  @@StartBracket@@passive/solid@@EndBracket@@. These are not the only possible moves though. Here's a quick overview:  A.  3...Qe6+  or  3...Qe5+  places the queen on a bad square. We should block the check with  4.Be2  and continue our development  with Nf3, d4, and kingside castling.   B.  3...Qd6  is not that bad and should be handled similarly to our main lines  3...Qd8  and  3...Qa5  . We play a setup  with d4 and Nf3, just like in the main lines of the current chapter.   C.  3...Qc6??  4.Bb5  is a sad end to the queen's adventure.   Now, Black's most important queen moves are to d8 and a5. In both cases, we must be aware that to fight for an advantage successfully, we must proceed energetically. Black will often answer our natural move Nf3 with a bishop pin ...Bg4, when we need to start a promising attack on the kingside.  This is a case where knowing general opening principles is not quite enough; you need to know how to punish Black's setup. We'll have a look at how to do it! }
3... Qd8
{ Back home! It is a more cautious move than  3...Qa5  , as Black's queen is in a safe spot. Our strategy against both queen moves is quite similar. We want to play our  pawn to d4 and develop our knight to f3, very natural play. After that, we must adjust according to Black's concept. }
4. d4 Nf6
{ Black's most flexible move. They develop the knight to the most active square and won't yet commit to a pawn formation. Black can play many other moves, of course. None of them are particularly active though.   Against a move like  4...e6  , we continue with our development concept  of Nf3, Bc4, and castling kingside. }
5. Nf3
{ We develop our knights to the natural squares. Now Black usually opts for the active bishop move to g4, pinning our knight. }
5... Bg4
{ This move is in line with the spirit of the Scandinavian. Black wants to develop their bishop actively, and then continue with ...e6 and develop the kingside next. We have reached an important moment, as the difference between the correct and less critical approaches is huge. What we need to do is fight against the pin immediately. }
6. h3
{ A continuation like  6.Be2?!  is too passive. Black has no problems completing their development. We need to play more aggressively. }
6... Bh5
{ Black should prefer  6...Bxf3  , but  7.Qxf3  c6  @@StartBracket@@b7 was hanging@@EndBracket@@  8.Be3  is nice for White. We have the bishop pair in an open position and a good choice between castling kingside @@StartBracket@@solid@@EndBracket@@, or queenside @@StartBracket@@aggressive@@EndBracket@@. }
7. g4
{ We need to get rid of the pin and start a quick attack on the kingside. }
7... Bg6 8. Ne5
{ The point. Now we are ready for multiple ideas.  We can play h4, threatening h4-h5. Bg2 comes with a tempo on b7. We can castle queenside later. Black is under strong pressure, supported by White's fantastic score.    A sample line is  8...e6  9.Bg2  c6  10.h4  ,  when h4-h5 is already a terrible threat. Black usually responds by moving their h-pawn, but something like  10...h6  11.Nxg6  fxg6  12.Qd3  leads to devastation. Black's kingside is in ruins. }
