2. exd5
{ The best move by far. Black needs to invest some time to regain the pawn. Now we will focus on  2...Qxd5  , Black's most popular reply. You also meet  2...Nf6  , which we will check briefly too. }
2... Qxd5
{ Black has 'developed' the queen, but it is a target for our knight. } 3. Nc3
{ Here we go! We get our piece into the game while Black is forced to move the queen a second time. Where does it go? We'll look at the most popular options:  3...Qa5  @@StartBracket@@active@@EndBracket@@, and  3...Qd8  @@StartBracket@@passive/solid@@EndBracket@@. These are not the only possible moves though. Here's a quick overview:  A.  3...Qe6+  or  3...Qe5+  places the queen on a bad square. We should block the check with  4.Be2  and continue our development  with Nf3, d4, and kingside castling.   B.  3...Qd6  is not that bad and should be handled similarly to our main lines  3...Qd8  and  3...Qa5  . We play a setup  with d4 and Nf3, just like in the main lines of the current chapter.   C.  3...Qc6??  4.Bb5  is a sad end to the queen's adventure.   Now, Black's most important queen moves are to d8 and a5. In both cases, we must be aware that to fight for an advantage successfully, we must proceed energetically. Black will often answer our natural move Nf3 with a bishop pin ...Bg4, when we need to start a promising attack on the kingside.  This is a case where knowing general opening principles is not quite enough; you need to know how to punish Black's setup. We'll have a look at how to do it! }
3... Qa5
{ A more active queen position than d8, but also more exposed. We'll see that Black's queen can get into trouble if they are not careful. Our first steps are easy now: we play d4 and Nf3, developing and occupying the center. }
4. d4
{ We want to play the pawn move first. Starting with the knight move to f3 is not a blunder, of course. But from a general concept point of view, it is more urgent to place a pawn in the center, if allowed. }
4... Nf6
{ You'll also meet  4...c6  frequently. Black creates some retreat squares for the queen this way. Against this move, we'll play in the same spirit as against  4...Nf6  .  We develop your knight to f3 and see how Black develops. If they play ...Bg4, we go for the throat with h3&g4. A sample line to show this concept is  4...c6  5.Nf3  Bg4  6.h3  Bh5  7.g4  Bg6  8.Ne5  , just the same idea as after @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  . This kingside play is well justified, as you'll see in the notes to our main move in a moment. }
5. Nf3
{ The natural spot for our knight. Now Black has two main ideas to go for. They usually want to develop their c8-bishop actively and choose between going to f5 or g4. We'll focus on ...Bg4, as this move requires an energetic response. }
5... Bg4
{ Going for the pin is the most popular and active move, but it is a risky choice. Black hopes that we respond passively, but we won't comply!   Before we examine  5...Bg4  , a word about Black's alternatives. They also go for a setup based  on ...Bf5, either by playing  5...Bf5  immediately or  5...c6  and only  later decide on a square for the c8-bishop. In both cases, we should develop our bishop to c4. Let's have a look:   A.  5...Bf5  6.Bc4  ,  followed by a later Bd2 to threaten discoveries by our knight. A good, sharper alternative is  6.Ne5  ,  planning a quick g2-g4!   B.  5...c6  6.Bc4  , when  6...Bf5  is well met by  7.Bd2  or  7.Ne5  , with good chances for White. If Black opts for @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/q7/2BP4/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bg4  ,  going for h3&g4 is strong, just as in the main line we are about to examine now. }
6. h3
{ Very important to remember: we want to react aggressively to Black's pin. A move like  6.Be2?!  is lame and gives Black an easy game. Just compare it to the trouble that we create for our opponent now. After  6.h3  , they either have to gift us the bishop pair or retreat. }
6... Bh5
{ Black's usual choice, keeping the pin. Taking on f3 is a sad decision and unpopular, but what about the funny move  6...Qh5?  This is a blunder, but the refutation is not so easy to spot. It is  6...Qh5??  7.hxg4!!  Qxh1  and now  8.Ne2!  sets up the  deadly knight jump Ng3, winning the queen! A cool way to win! Note that  8...Ne4  9.Qd3  does not help Black. }
7. g4 { That's the idea. We break the pin and expand on the kingside. } 7...
Bg6 8. Ne5
{ This final move is an important point. Black has to be careful now, as we threaten to attack Black's bishop with h4-h5, but we may also play Nc4, when Black's queen is running short of squares.   A cool line to demonstrate this plan is the following:  8...Nbd7  9.Nc4  Qa6  and now  10.Bf4  ,  when we threaten Nd6+, winning the queen. Black is under huge pressure and has to defend very accurately to stay in the game. It's crucial to fight Black's ...Bg4 ideas aggressively. These positions are excellent for White, while passive continuations easily let Black off the hook.  Conclusion: The Scandinavian is popular on the amateur level because White often fails to play energetically enough. We have seen that powerful play gives us excellent early attacking chances.  The whole sequence of h3, g4, and Ne5 is a good example of opening play that does not quite comply with the general opening principles 1 to 4 that we discussed before. However, it perfectly aligns with principle 5, which translates to 'concrete beats the abstract'. Our play directly addresses the deficits of Black's play: the insecure queen position and the offside bishop on the kingside. }
