[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) Pirc/Modern Defense 1.e4 d6/g6"]
[Black "Modern Defense 1.e4 g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6
{ Black starts with  1...g6  , the kingside fianchetto. This opening is often called the 'Modern Defense', even though it is decades old by now. :-@@EndBracket@@ In the Modern Defense, Black allows White to establish a strong pawn center and tries to attack it later. We'll consider these ideas in more detail  on move 3. }
2. d4 { Alright, let's take the center. } 2... Bg7 3. Nc3
{ White has a wide choice, as there is no immediate pressure on our center. Against all early ...g6 lines, I suggest a setup based on Nc3, f4, Nf3, and Bd3. This broad center is an excellent foundation for an attack in the middle of the board @@StartBracket@@e4-e5@@EndBracket@@ and the kingside.   After  3.Nc3  , Black has a wide range of setups.  If they play a quick ...d6 and ...Nf6, we'll transpose to the Pirc Defense, a close relative of the Modern. We cover the Pirc  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  in the current chapter too.  Black may delay ...Nf6 and go for ...d6, followed by ...a6 and ...b5 for a queenside expansion. Or they may prefer a defensive formation with ...b6, ...d6, and ...e6, the so-called 'Hippopotamus'. The beauty of the f4-based approach is: it works well against all of these ideas. We'll have a look at one of them. }
3... d6 4. f4 e6
{ Black is aiming for ...Ne7, which keeps the long diagonal open. After  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  , we'd transpose to the Pirc Defense.   Instead of  4...e6  , Black may play various other 'small moves'. After  4...a6  5.Nf3  b5  6.Bd3  , we have reached our standard formation, with good chances due  to a later @@StartBracket@@or sooner!@@EndBracket@@ e4-e5 advance. Playing e4-e5 is a powerful idea, as it blunts the g7-bishop and secures an advantage in space. }
5. Nf3 { We want to play Nf3, Bd3, and castle next. } 5... Ne7 6. Bd3 O-O 7.
O-O
{ We have completed our intended setup and can be happy about our chances. Our pawn center is well-supported and an excellent base for an attack. A good idea worth knowing is Qe1-h4, getting our strongest attacker closer to the enemy king. }
