[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) Pirc/Modern Defense 1.e4 d6/g6"]
[Black "Pirc Defense 1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6
{ In this chapter, we will examine setups for Black based on the early moves ...g6 or ...d6. A typical sequence is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  , called the 'Pirc Defense'. Black plays  a pawn to d6 to stop our e-pawn from advancing and intends to castle kingside quickly. Black does not fight for the center with an early pawn move but prefers to give White a pawn center and plans to attack it later, often by pushing the c-pawn or e-pawn.   Black's setup does not put any early pressure on our center, which gives us a wide range of possible pawn and piece configurations to choose from. Against the early ...d6/...g6 system, I recommend a more aggressive setup, including an early push of the f-pawn. Using the f-pawn in the early opening stage is often risky, as it does not help development and might weaken the king. Here these concerns don't apply, as Black's forces are too modestly placed to exploit these defects. Let's discuss the benefits of an early f4 once it is on the board. }
2. d4
{ The natural move. Black didn't prevent it, so we occupied the center with both pawns. }
2... Nf6
{ Black attacks our e-pawn, a threat that we can easily meet with a move we wanted to play anyway. }
3. Nc3
{ It is important to avoid  3.e5?  dxe5  4.dxe5  Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  Ng4  , when we would lose a pawn. Black played 1...d6 to prevent the early advance of the e-pawn. }
3... g6
{ The fianchetto is the logical companion of the move ...d6. How else to develop the kingside?   There is an alternative in  3...e5  , but this move has little independent significance. The best reply is  4.Nf3  , when we transpose to positions that we examine via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  , which is the Philidor Defense.   If Black plays any other 'small' move, like  3...g6  ,  3...c6  ,  3...e6  , or similarly passive ideas,  I suggest playing f4! to build a powerful pawn formation. }
4. f4
{ This is the only case of an early f-pawn move in our repertoire. Why is it strong here? The key idea is that we would like to start an attack in the center with e4-e5, but we need more support for this pawn push @@StartBracket@@note how @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5?  failed@@EndBracket@@. We plan to complete the  following setup: f4, Nf3, Bd3, O-O, and finally, e4-e5. starting our attack. A great upside of this aggressive plan is that it works well against all Black's defenses that don't challenge our center. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3 { We want to complete our kingside development first. } 5...
O-O 6. Bd3
{ This is the best square for our bishop. Playing  6.Bc4?  is worse because Black has the surprising move  6...Nxe4!  , when  7.Nxe4  d5  regains the piece. Black managed to remove our e-pawn, which is a huge accomplishment. Our whole setup is based  on playing e4-e5, after all!   After our move  6.Bd3  , Black has some options. Here's a brief overview:  A.  6...Bg4  7.h3  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  gives White the bishop pair on top of the great center.   B.  6...Nbd7  7.e5!  pushes Black's knight  back to e8, which is a very passive post.   C.  6...c5  7.dxc5  dxc5  8.e5!  gains a lot of space and establishes a well-covered  pawn on e5, thus making the g7-bishop less effective. This is a key idea of our pawn advance.  Conclusion: If Black plays a setup based on ...d6, ...g6, moves that don't challenge our center, it is a good idea to involve our f-pawn early on and build a center of three powerful pawns. A key idea is advancing e4-e5, establishing a large space advantage in the center. This advanced pawn is bad news for Black's g7-bishop, which will often be passively placed. }
