[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) Alekhine & Others"]
[Black "Alekhine & Others 1.e4 Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Our final chapter deals with the 'Odds and Ends', the rare moves that Black may play. The most interesting and unique is  1...Nf6  , Alekhine's Defense. We'll have a closer look at this move and briefly talk about ever rarer alternatives for Black. }
1... Nf6
{ Well, our e-pawn is unprotected... so Black attacks it! The drawback of the move is clear: we can advance the pawn and push Black's knight around. Before we continue, a word about even less popular moves. These unpopular moves are exotic for a reason. They are less reliable than mainstream options or even violate basic opening principles. Let's have a very brief look.   A.  1...Nc6  is rare, but not that bad. After  2.Nf3  e5  , we may still transpose to a mainstream opening. If Black avoids  2...e5  , we'd happily continue with natural moves that follow the principles: occupy the center, develop the kingside and castle.   B.  1...b6  should also be answered with normal, central play. A natural continuation is  2.d4  Bb7  3.Bd3  or  3.Nc3  to cover our pawn. We'd continue with developing the kingside and castling.   C. Other moves look odd, like moving a rook pawn or weakening the position voluntarily with  1...f6?  or  1...g5?  − we'll just follow general opening principles against these bad moves. Develop, occupy the center, and castle quickly... and enjoy the game! }
2. e5
{ We gain space with a gain of time − this must be best. Covering the pawn with  2.Nc3  is no mistake, but less powerful, as Black's replies  2...e5  and  2...d5  look reasonable. }
2... Nd5 3. d4
{ You may also play  3.c4  Nb6  4.d4  , when  4...d6  5.exd6  leads to the same positions. }
3... d6
{ This move reveals Black's idea. They want to lure our pawns to advance and then attack our center. }
4. c4
{ Building a nice pawn center while attacking Black's quirky knight. White has an excellent alternative in  4.Nf3  , but I think my recommendation is a simpler choice and just as good. }
4... Nb6 5. exd6
{ This pawn capture has been my favorite line for years. It is simple to play but still gives White an advantage. The most aggressive alternative is  5.f4  , but this line requires detailed study. This learning effort is tough to justify because you'll almost never get it on the board. }
5... cxd6
{ Black has a choice between  5...exd6  and  5...cxd6  . Both moves are about equally popular but lead to different position types. Taking with the c-pawn leads to a non-symmetrical pawn structure, while  5...exd6  results in an open e-file and a symmetrical pawn distribution.   Still, both lines have one common feature: we have a strong center and more space. Our next step is to develop the kingside, castle, and support our center. We'd like to play Nf3, Be2, and O-O quickly in both scenarios. It's also possible to play the move h2-h3 early on, preventing the move ...Bg4. }
6. Nf3
{ We get one move closer to kingside castling and want to play Be2 and O-O soon. We'll usually complete our development with Nc3 and Be3 later.   The interesting point is that playing h2-h3 early is often useful, as Black finds it difficult to find a useful role for their bishop if ...Bg4 is prevented. After  6.Nf3  g6  for instance, playing  7.h3  is a strong move, despite looking a bit slow.  Conclusion: Alekhine's Defense allows White to build a strong center. Our setup is easy to play and features a logical development of our pieces. The knights reach their best squares quickly, and we manage to castle kingside to secure our king. }
