[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Andrei Volokitin − Pentala Harikrishna, Lausanne 2005"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This game, played between two top players from Ukraine and India, features a common pawn structure after  1.e4  e5  − let's discuss it further once it is on the board. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ Black opts for a slightly passive setup, Philidor Defense. The f8-bishop can't develop to an active post @@StartBracket@@c5, for example@@EndBracket@@ after the early ...d6. }
3. d4 { White increases the pressure on e5 and opens the center. } 3... exd4
{ Black's best move, as discussed in the chapter on this opening line. } 4.
Nxd4
{ This is the pawn structure I was referring to initially. After we played d2-d4, Black captured the pawn. The capture is generally the best response to our pawn advance, but a key point to discuss is the placement of Black's pawn on d6, locking in the bishop. Various possible move sequences lead to a similar formation.   A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  exd4  4.Nxd4  @@StartBracket@@this game@@EndBracket@@  B.  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nc3  d6  4.d4  exd4  5.Nxd4  @@StartBracket@@also reached in the game@@EndBracket@@  C.  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  d6  4.d4  exd4  5.Nxd4   D.  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.d4  d6  5.Bb5  exd4  6.Nxd4   E.  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.d4  exd4  5.Nxd4  d6   F.  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.d4  exd4  5.Nxd4  Nxd4  6.Qxd4  d6  7.Bf4  @@StartBracket@@this is like the game, but White is a tempo up, as we take on  d4  in one move!@@EndBracket@@  You see that there are a ton of possible moves that may lead us to a similar scenario. In all cases, I suggest the strategy employed in the main game − hang on. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7 6. Bf4
{ Black's setup is rather passive and doesn't put serious pressure on our center. Therefore, we can be more ambitious and aim for queenside castling. This is viewed as more 'ambitious', as it takes longer to complete than kingside castling. Our idea is to hide the king on the queenside to prepare an assault on the other side of the board. }
6... O-O 7. Qd2 Nc6
{ The most natural move. A bad idea is  7...c5?  8.Ndb5  , when we win the d-pawn. }
8. O-O-O
{ Mission accomplished, our king is safely placed on the queenside. This allows the advance of the kingside pawns, launching an attack on our opponent's king. }
8... Nxd4 9. Qxd4
{ Our queen is well placed in the center. Black could attack it with ...c5?, but it would only lead to a weak d6-pawn that we can attack easily. }
9... Be6
{ Much better than  9...c5?  10.Qe3  , when we have enormous pressure  on d6. }
10. f3 { A key move to prepare the advance of the g-pawn. } 10... Nd7
{ An interesting move. Black wants to play ...Bg5, trading the passive bishop for our more active one. How to stop this idea? }
11. Qe3
{ I like this move to preserve our bishop and keep Black's piece passive. }
11... Qb8
{ A bit slow. Black was probably concerned about the queen being opposite White's rook on the d-file.   Harikrishna plays ...Ne5 on the next move, which was not possible right away due to  11...Ne5??  12.Bxe5  , winning the knight.   Still, it was better to go  11...Bf6  to activate the bishop. We start our attack after  12.g4  Qe7  13.h4  , but Black's formation is still solid. }
12. g4 { Here we go − our game is easy to play. } 12... Ne5 13. h4 c6
{ Black prepares ...b5, but it is obvious that our pawn storm is quicker. } 14.
g5 b5 15. Bg3
{ We move the bishop to free our f-pawn. The push f4-f5 would hit two black pieces in the process. }
15... Qb6
{ A good decision. Black fears getting into a deadly attack on the kingside and wants to trade queens to reduce the danger. }
16. Qxb6
{ We don't mind the trade, as the resulting position is still favorable for us. }
16... axb6 17. f4 { Keeping the initiative. } 17... Ng4
{ Black has to play this move, as  17...b4  18.fxe5  bxc3  19.exd6  cxb2+  20.Kb1!  Bd8  21.Bh3  Bxa2+  22.Kxb2  is great for White due to the monster d-pawn. }
18. f5 { A strong move, keeping the pressure up. Now what? } 18... Bxa2
{ Black's only real mistake in the game! The computer finds  18...b4!  19.Ne2  Bc8!  , which only allows a small advantage for White. We have lots of space after  20.Nd4  and still a dangerous initiative, but Black is in the game. }
19. Bxd6 Bxd6 20. Rxd6
{ Now we see the problem. Black's queenside pawns are vulnerable, and the a2-bishop is in danger of getting trapped. If Black played  20...Ne5  now,  21.b3!  is decisive. }
20... b4 21. Nd1
{ Again, we threaten b2-b3 to trap the bishop. Black has to react. } 21... b3
22. c3
{ There was nothing wrong about  22.Rxc6  , but Volokitin prefers to keep Black's bishop in its unlucky spot. It has no square to go to. }
22... Ra4 23. Bd3 { White has time to cover e4. } 23... Rfa8 24. Kd2
{ A good move. White recognizes that the king would be safe on d2 and, at the same time, help to organize the position. It takes away squares from the g4-knight, for example. }
24... Kf8 25. Rd4
{ Or  25.Ke2  , which was just as good. Black is playing without  the a2-bishop, which is a permanent problem. }
25... c5 26. Rxa4 Rxa4 27. Rf1
{ White has spotted that  27.Ne3?  Nf2  is annoying and stops this resource. }
27... b5 28. Ne3 Nxe3 { Or  28...Ne5  29.Nd5  , which wins for White too. } 29.
Kxe3 c4 30. Be2
{ The conversion to a full point is quite easy here, as Black is playing a piece down. The only resource is a possible ...b5-b4 breakthrough. }
30... Ra8
{ After  30...b4  31.Kd4!  bxc3  32.Kxc3  , any counterplay is stopped. } 31.
Rd1 Re8 32. f6 b4 33. Kd4
{ There is no need to allow  33.cxb4  c3  , with some counter chances. } 33...
gxf6 34. gxf6 Re6 35. e5 bxc3 36. Kxc3 Rxe5 37. Rd8+ Re8 38. Rxe8+ Kxe8 39.
Bxc4
{ The smoke has cleared to a completely winning bishop endgame. White picks up the b-pawn and obtains a decisive passed pawn. }
39... h6 40. Bxb3 Bb1 41. Kd4
{ White wins easily by pushing the b-pawn up the board. Black cannot defend, as the f7-pawn is an additional weakness.  Conclusion: This game shows that White gets a dangerous initiative by castling queenside and starting a pawn storm. Black is under pressure and faces a difficult defensive task. Harikrishna defended well, but one mistake was enough to get him into a lost endgame. }
