[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Jacek Szwed − Oleg Romanishin, Colonia de Sant Jordi 2023"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This game features Jacek Szwed, a Polish FM, and Oleg Romanishin, a living legend of Ukrainian chess. He was a top player in the 1970s and 1980s and famous for his imaginative attacking style. He's still an active tournament player today, competing in open events mostly. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Bc5
{ Romanishin is the only strong GM who has regularly employed this dubious line. Maybe this recent @@StartBracket@@played in June 2023@@EndBracket@@ game will be a 'cure' for this 'addiction'. }
4. Nxe5
{ The key idea for White, as discussed in the theoretical chapter. We give up the knight but will immediately win it back under favorable circumstances. }
4... Nxe5 5. d4 Bd6
{ This is Black's best bet after 4.Nxe5, the alternatives are even worse. Please see the theoretical chapter for information on these options for Black. }
6. dxe5 Bxe5 7. Bd3 Nf6 8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5
{ This is the final position of our theoretical chapter. Black is under pressure, as their knight is pinned, and White has a lead in development and more space. }
9... h6
{ Romanishin opts for a drastic solution. He wants to play ...h6 and ...g5 to drive White's bishop back. We'll see that this idea fails spectacularly, so it makes sense to examine alternatives.   A.  9...d6  10.f4  Bxc3  11.bxc3  Qe7  12.Qf3  is great for White.  We intend Ra1-e1, followed by e4-e5 if allowed. Black is under severe pressure.   B.  9...Qe8!  is the computer suggestion, but I don't see many human players going for this strange sidestep. Black wants to answer  10.f4?  with  10...Bxc3  11.bxc3  Nxe4  , but White can easily improve. Funny enough, @@StartFEN@@r1b1qrk1/pppp1ppp/5n2/4b1B1/4P3/2NB4/PPP2PPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 6 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Qe1!  seems to be best, setting  up f2-f4 again! }
10. Bh4 g5
{ That was the idea, but it loses to a powerful reply! Black had to try  10...Qe8  , but it's clearly not fun to play. }
11. f4
{ Wait, what? Yes, this move is possible, and a killer blow! Before we go into the details, note that the pedestrian move  11.Bg3  is better for White too. Black's kingside is weak, and White has a much easier job. White considered this easy option but then found the ingenious concept played in the game. Let's check some possible defensive attempts.   A.  11...Bxc3  12.fxg5  was played in the game.   B.  11...gxh4  12.fxe5  Nh7  13.Qh5  wins.   C.  11...gxf4  12.g3!  fxg3  13.Qf3  is deadly,  with Nd5 to come.   D.  11...Bxf4  12.Rxf4!  gxf4  13.Nd5  is a quick win too.   E.  11...Bd4+  12.Bf2  is great for White, as we trade Black's bishop, and their kingside is in ruins. }
11... Bxc3 12. fxg5 Bd4+
{ Here,  12...hxg5  13.bxc3  gxh4  14.e5  was the alternative, but it loses even faster than the game move. }
13. Kh1 Nh7
{ Or  13...hxg5  14.Bxg5  , when the pin is deadly again. After  14...Re8  15.Qe1  is strong,  aiming for Qh4. }
14. e5
{ A powerful move, opening the bishop.  14.Qh5  was the other winning shot, as Black's weak king can't be defended anymore. }
14... Nxg5
{ After  14...Bxe5  , White has multiple wins, such as  15.Qh5  Nxg5  16.Qxh6  @@StartBracket@@like in the game@@EndBracket@@, or simply @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pppp1p1n/7p/4b1P1/7B/3B4/PPP3PP/R2Q1R1K w - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Bxh7+  , as  15...Kxh7  16.g6+  shows. }
15. Qh5 Bxe5 16. Qxh6 Bg7 17. Qh5
{ White does not want to trade queens by going  17.Qxg5??  , but plays for mate. }
17... f5 18. Bxf5
{ Here  18.Rxf5  was even quicker, but the result is not in doubt. } 18... Qf6
19. Bxg5 Qxf5
{ Romanishin gives up the queen to stop mate, but it's a lost cause. } 20. Rxf5
Rxf5 21. Qg6 d6 22. Bh6 Rf7 23. Bxg7 Rxg7 24. Qe8+ Kh7 25. Re1
{ White's rook joins with decisive effect. A fantastic attacking game by Szwed! The move @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pppp1p2/5n1p/4b1p1/4P2B/2NB4/PPP2PPP/R2Q1RK1 w - g6 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.f4  completely refuted Black's concept and showed how risky the kingside  expansion ...h6/...g5 is. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Jorden van Foreest − Alexei Fedorov, Wch Blitz Almaty 2022"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ The game between GM Jorden van Foreest and GM Alexei Fedorov was played at a Blitz time control. Studying faster time control games can make a lot of sense. It is tougher to defend in Blitz, which sometimes leads to more one-sided games that help to illustrate key ideas. Let's examine how the Dutch No.2 quickly gained a winning attack against his fellow GM from Belarus. }
1... c5 2. c3 d6 3. d4
{ We are happy about being allowed to build the perfect center. } 3... Nf6 4.
Bd3 Qc7
{ In the theoretical chapter, we focus on  4...g6  , which looks like a better choice. Fedorov continues  with ...g6 on the next move, leading to a similar position. Placing the queen on c7 first is unnecessary and might backfire for Black  A key idea of the kingside fianchetto is putting some pressure on d4. With the queen on c7, opening the c-file by trading on d4 becomes less attractive. This issue will become more apparent later in the game. }
5. Nf3 g6 6. h3
{ White stops ...Bg4, which makes it more difficult for Black to find a good spot for the bishop. We have already seen this idea in the theoretical chapter. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1
{ A very natural setup for White. We enjoy the perfect pawn center and easily find good spots for our minor pieces. This is a huge benefit of controlling the center. We have more space and options for our pieces, while Black struggles to complete development and initiate any active play. }
8... Nfd7
{ This looks wrong, but Black's life wasn't easy. He was worried about the advance e4-e5 and decided to move the knight again to stop this idea. Any alternatives?   A.  8...e5  stops White's e-pawn but blocks  Black's g7-bishop. We have more than one good reply, but I like to complete the development.  9.Be3  Nbd7  10.Nbd2  is my suggestion. We can try for a queenside offensive later,  including b2-b4.   B.  8....Nbd7  9.e5  @@StartBracket@@or a simple development like  9.Nbd2  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppqnppbp/3p1np1/2p1P3/3P4/2PB1N1P/PP3PP1/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nd5  10.Be4  N5b6  11.Bf4  looks dangerous for Black.   C.  8...cxd4?  9.cxd4  is great for us, as we can develop  our knight to c3. Black's queen is badly placed, as mentioned in the fourth move notes. It may be hit by Nb1-c3-b5 or a rook coming to the c-file later. }
9. Bg5 { Van Foreest develops the bishop and attacks e7 − a good move. } 9...
Nc6 { Black's best reply, attacking d4 and covering e7. } 10. Na3
{ A strong move. The alternative  10.d5  looks attractive, but  10...Nce5  11.Bxe7?  Nxf3+  is a problem. After  12.Qxf3??  Ne5  , Black wins a piece, and @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppqnBpbp/3p2p1/2pP4/4P3/2PB1n1P/PP3PP1/RN1QR1K1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.gxf3  weakens White's king position. Therefore, taking  the e7-pawn is a bad idea. Van Foreest's move is stronger, as it keeps the central tension. }
10... a6
{ What about the d4-pawn? Black could have played  10...cxd4  11.cxd4  Nxd4  12.Nxd4  Bxd4  , but  13.Bxe7  Re8  14.Bg5  Bxb2  15.Nb5  Qc6  16.Rb1  gives White a huge initiative for the pawn. Black correctly decides against this greedy pawn grab and prefers a cautious move. }
11. Nc2 { White covers d4 and prepares the knight to transfer to e3. } 11...
Re8 12. Qd2
{ It's easy to play the White side. Black has no pressure on the center, giving White all the time to connect rooks and prepare more direct action. }
12... b5 { Black finally tries to develop their c8-bishop. } 13. Ne3
{ Here we go. The knight not only looks at the d5-square but gets closer to the kingside too. }
13... e6 { Black can only stop one idea. } 14. Ng4
{ It's getting serious now − White's pieces get closer to the king. How to defend? }
14... h5
{ This already loses the game! Black had to try  14...e5  , taking control of  the f4-square. White is still much better but it won't end as quickly as the game. A good way to continue for White is  15.Nh6+  Kf8  16.a4!  , trying to open the a-file. There is no direct mating attack, so we must involve more pieces,  like the a1-rook. }
15. Nh6+ Kf8
{ A very sad move, but  15...Bxh6  16.Bxh6  can't work out either. Black's king position is too shaky. }
16. Qf4 { Going for the kill. } 16... f6 17. Nh4
{ Very nice! White threatens a beautiful mate now. Can Black stop Nxg6#? }
17... Nde5 { Fedorov covers g6, but... } 18. dxe5 Nxe5 19. Qxe5
{ Boom! White still threatens mate, as  19...dxe5  20.Nxg6#  shows! Black can't take the queen and might as well have resigned here. }
19... Ke7 20. Bxf6+ Kd7
{ Or  20...Bxf6  21.Nxg6+  Kd7  22.Qxf6  , winning the house. } 21. Qg5
{ And Black resigned. He's two pieces down and is still in danger of being checkmated. A nice attacking display by Jorden van Foreest showing that it is easier to attack if you have a great foundation out of the opening.   Controlling the center and developing all your pieces makes it look easy sometimes. Black only made one substantial mistake and was immediately lost! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Monika Socko − Per Ofstad, Helsingør 2008"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ All roads lead to Rome... and many more orders may lead to the same position. This game between GM Monika Socko and Per Ofstad did NOT start with  1.e4!  The real moves were:  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.cxd5  cxd5  4.Nc3  Nc6  5.e4  e6  6.e5  Bd7  7.Nf3  , when they reached a position that we discuss via  1.e4  c5  2.c3  e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.cxd4  d5  5.e5  Nc6  6.Nf3  Bd7  7.Nc3  − a remarkable transposition! I have adjusted the moves to match the course. }
1... c5 2. c3 e6 3. d4 cxd4
{ Black should postpone this trade and play  3...d5!  − see the theoretical section for details. }
4. cxd4 d5 5. e5 Nc6 6. Nf3 Bd7 7. Nc3
{ This move highlights the drawback of the early pawn trade. White gains this excellent square for the knight. }
7... Qb6
{ Black increases the pressure on d4. White's next move is important and a key resource to remember. }
8. a3
{ Why is it a strong move? Don't we have more pressing things to do, like developing pieces? That is a valid point, but developing our bishops on good squares is difficult. The c1-bishop needs to guard the b-pawn, and  8.Bd3?  Nxd4!  blunders a pawn.   You can play  8.Be2  , but we'd much prefer the bishop  on d3, pointing to the kingside. Black's queen and knight exert annoying pressure on d4. We want to take care of this pressure first, then develop our bishops to the best squares.   A way to do it is  8.Na4  , but Black has  8...Bb4+  9.Bd2  Bxd2+  10.Qxd2  Qb4  , when they manage to trade some pieces. This ultimately leads us to @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/pp1b1ppp/1qn1p3/3pP3/3P4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8.a3!  ,  which aims at playing Na4 with greater effect. Let's continue the game to see how it unfolds. }
8... Rc8 9. Na4
{ Now Black can't play ...Bb4+ and  9...Qa5+?  10.b4  makes no sense either. }
9... Qc7 { The queen has to retreat, reducing the pressure on our d-pawn. } 10.
Be3
{ In the theoretical section, I recommended  10.Bd3  , which looks more natural. Ultimately, the bishops will likely be placed  on d3 and e3 anyway. }
10... b5
{ Black goes for an imaginative defense. It looks like they blundered the b-pawn, but it's not that easy. }
11. Nc3
{ After  12.Bxb5  Nxe5!  13.Bxd7+  Nxd7  , Black regains the pawn, a funny tactic! This wouldn't be a bad position for White, but retreating the knight is stronger, as it keeps more pieces on the board. In general, this is a good strategy if you control more space. The more cramped side has too many pieces for a few squares and aims to trade material.   In the current position, Black has problems with the kingside pieces. Their knight and bishop would like to use e7, but this is just one square for two pieces. For White, developing our minor pieces to active squares is much easier. }
11... a6 12. Bd3
{ The best square for the bishop, looking at both sides of the board. } 12...
Be7
{ It's tough for Black to develop. After  12...Nge7  13.O-O  Ng6  , I suggest  14.h4!  Be7  15.h5  to start the attack. Black does not manage to castle and has poor piece coordination. }
13. O-O h5
{ It looks dubious, but  13...Nh6  14.Bxh6  gxh6  15.Qd2  is no improvement. }
14. Rc1 { Socko has all the time in the world to improve. } 14... Qd8
{ It looks like Black is thinking about ...g5, starting a desperate kingside action. }
15. a4
{ A very logical choice. The development is finished, time to start some action and open the game. }
15... b4 16. Ne2 a5 { Black saves the a-pawn. } 17. Qd2
{ If you see a move with multiple purposes, it will often be strong! This one is no exception. The queen move connects the rooks to prepare to double on the c-file. At the same time, it stops any ...g5 ideas. }
17... Nh6 { Finally, getting the knight out. } 18. b3
{ Much better than  18.Rc2?!  b3!  , when Black gains  access to b4 with a gain of tempo. White is in no rush. }
18... Ng4 19. Bf4 { No trades for you! } 19... Rg8
{ Okay... we see what Black wants to do. Should White stop ...g5? } 20. Ng5
{ Yes, there is no need to allow Black any activity. Something like  20.h3  g5  starts to look murky. }
20... Bxg5
{ Black wants to get rid of the dangerous knight. Note that  20...f6??  21.Bg6+  Kf8  22.Nh7#  is a funny end! }
21. Bxg5 f6
{ After  21...Qb6  22.Rc5  , Black can't play  22...Nxd4  23.Rxc8+  Bxc8  24.Nxd4  Qxd4  25.Bb5+  , allowing a common tactical trick. }
22. Bg6+ Ke7 23. Bxh5 { Black is falling apart quickly now. } 23... Nxh2
{ A witty response, but Socko finds a convincing reply. } 24. Qf4
{ Instead,  24.Kxh2  Rh8  is still somewhat irritating. The move played in the game is much simpler. White threatens to  take f6 and  24...fxg5??  25.Qxg5  Kf8  26.Qf4  Ke7  27.Qf7#  doesn't help. }
24... Qf8 { Black covers f6, but it's beyond saving for a while already. } 25.
exf6+ gxf6 26. Bh6 Qd8 27. Kxh2
{ Finally taking the lone knight. White is a piece up and has a crushing attack on top. The rest is easy. }
27... Be8 28. Bf3 e5 29. dxe5 Nxe5 30. Nd4 Bd7 31. Kg1 Rg6 32. Bh5 Rg8 33. Rce1
Qc7 34. Nf3
{ Monika Socko nicely demonstrated how to handle White's advantage in space. Black has problems developing their kingside, while White can play on both sides of the board.  Black tried a desperate kingside action in the game, but it backfired badly. Note how White took the time to stop the opponent's possible ideas first. If your opponent's activity is reduced, your attack will be much simpler to conduct. }
