[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Artyom Timofeev − Peter Svidler, Moscow 2008"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Peter Svidler has won a total of eight @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ Russian Championships. The following game was played in one of these, the 2008 edition. He won the event, but not this particular game. His opponent, Artyom Timofeev, handled the Isolated Queen Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@ structure excellently.  The IQP structure can arise from multiple lines of our repertoire, like the Caro-Kann, the French, or the Sicilian. Let's have a look at how to handle these structures. }
1... c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4
{ The Panov Attack, our weapon against the Caro-Kann. } 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6.
Nf3 Bb4 7. Bd3 dxc4 8. Bxc4 O-O 9. O-O
{ Our theoretical section covers the opening play up to this point. Here Black has a choice between different setups. }
9... b6
{ Svidler opts for the quicky queenside fianchetto. A different idea is  9...Nc6  , developing the knight first. We'd react in the same way as White played in the game. A good way to develop  is Bg5 and Re1 and then decide how to continue. Sometimes Black opts for ...a6 and ...b5, when playing Rc1 makes sense, just as in the game. Sample variations in the theoretical section illustrate this idea. }
10. Bg5 { A very natural and active move, pinning Black's knight. } 10... Bb7
11. Re1
{ The rook is well placed on e1. A key idea for White is d4-d5 at the right moment, opening the center. In this case, the rook is perfectly placed on the open e-file. }
11... Nbd7
{ An interesting choice. Black may also play  11...Nc6  12.a3  Be7  , when I suggest  13.Qd3  Rc8  14.Rad1  ,  intending Bc4-a2-b1 to aim at the kingside. }
12. Rc1 Rc8
{ Both sides place their rooks on the open file. One idea of ...Nbd7 was to play this move with tempo, attacking our bishop. }
13. Qb3
{ Attacking and defending simultaneously is usually a good idea. White covers the c4-bishop with a gain of time. }
13... Bxc3
{ A tough decision. The alternative is  13...Be7  , preserving the bishop. This may lead to some cool tactics.  14.Bxf6  Nxf6  15.Bxe6!  is possible and featured in a famous game between Kramnik and Kasparov in their World Championship match. After  15...fxe6  16.Qxe6  Kh8  @@StartBracket@@  16...Rf7??  17.Ne5  wins@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2rq1r1k/pb2b1pp/1p2Qn2/8/3P4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/2R1R1K1 w - - 1 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Qxe7  Bxf3  18.gxf3  Qxd4  , White was a pawn up in a complicated position. Kasparov soon blundered and lost this important game.  The important takeaway from this line is: always check the most aggressive and tactical moves, like the bishop sacrifice  on e6. In IQP positions, the side with the isolated pawn should play as actively as possible and use the mobility of the pieces. The IQP side wants to keep pieces on the board and complicate, while the defending side aims to trade pieces and reach an endgame to target the isolated pawn. }
14. Rxc3
{ The most logical capture, keeping the rook active. In addition,  14.bxc3?!  Bxf3  15.gxf3  looks quite ugly for White. }
14... Rc7
{ This turns out to be a serious mistake. Black's position was not easy to play though. Stockfish suggests  14...h6  15.Bh4  Qe8  to unpin, but White still retains an initiative after  16.Qa3  , when the bishop pair is a long-term asset. I'd prefer White, but the engine claims it is equal. }
15. Ne5
{ Not only centralizing the knight but also preparing to swing the rook to g3 or h3! Now Black is in mortal danger. }
15... Kh8
{ This loses by force. The best attempt was  15...h6  , when  16.Nxf7!  Rxf7  17.Bxe6  Nf8  is better for White, but Black is not getting checkmated! }
16. Rh3 { Here we go! } 16... Qa8
{ The move  16...Bd5  may lose similarly to the game.  17.Nxd7  Rxd7  18.Qa3  Bxc4  19.Bxf6  gxf6  20.Rxh7+!  crushes Black. }
17. Nxd7 Rxd7
{ Here  17...Nxd7  was a bit tougher, but there is no defense against best play. One way for White is  18.Qd3  g6  19.Bb5  , threatening to capture the knight and invade  with Bf6+.  After  19...Bc6  20.Qg3!  is strong. White attacks the rook and wants to  play Qh4 next. This is far too much to handle. }
18. Bxf6
{ Timofeev has calculated to the end. He removes the knight to prepare the final blow. }
18... gxf6 19. Rxh7+
{ Very nice! Here Svidler resigned, as  19...Kxh7  20.Qh3+  Kg7  21.Qg4+  Kh6  22.Re3  is deadly − Black's king can't escape. A great game by Timofeev, taking down his famous opponent.  We have witnessed that White's active pieces are dangerous, and Black's position is tricky to play. Always remember that you want to play as actively as possible and keep posing problems with as many pieces on the board as possible. Don't trade, but look for attacking chances! }
*

